# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biomass
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The **activated sludge** **process** is a type of biological wastewater treatment process for treating sewage or industrial wastewaters using aeration and a biological floc composed of bacteria and protozoa.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] It is one of several biological wastewater treatment alternatives in secondary treatment, which deals with the removal of biodegradable organic matter and suspended solids.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] It uses air (or oxygen) and microorganisms to biologically oxidize organic pollutants, producing a waste sludge (or floc) containing the oxidized material.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The activated sludge process for removing carbonaceous pollution begins with an aeration tank where air (or oxygen) is injected into the waste water.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] This is followed by a settling tank to allow the biological flocs (the sludge blanket) to settle, thus separating the biological sludge from the clear treated water.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Part of the waste sludge is recycled to the aeration tank and the remaining waste sludge is removed for further treatment and ultimate disposal.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Plant types include package plants, oxidation ditch, deep shaft/vertical treatment, surface-aerated basins, and sequencing batch reactors (SBRs).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Aeration methods include diffused aeration, surface aerators (cones) or, rarely, pure oxygen aeration.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Sludge bulking can occur which makes activated sludge difficult to settle and frequently has an adverse impact on final effluent quality.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Treating sludge bulking and managing the plant to avoid a recurrence requires skilled management and may require full-time staffing of a works to allow immediate intervention.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] A new development of the activated sludge process is the Nereda process which produces a granular sludge that settles very well.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The activated sludge process is a biological process used to oxidise carbonaceous biological matter, oxidising nitrogenous matter (mainly ammonium and nitrogen) in biological matter, and removing nutrients (nitrogen and phosphorus).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The process takes advantage of aerobic micro-organisms that can digest organic matter in sewage, and clump together by flocculation entrapping fine particulate matter as they do so.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] It thereby produces a liquid that is relatively free from suspended solids and organic material, and flocculated particles that will readily settle out and can be removed.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Treatment of nitrogenous or phosphorous matter comprises the addition of an anoxic compartment inside the aeration tank in order to perform the nitrification-denitrification process more efficiently.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] First, ammonia is oxidized to nitrite, which is then converted into nitrate in aerobic conditions (aeration compartment).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Facultative bacteria then reduce the nitrate to nitrogen gas in anoxic conditions (anoxic compartment).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Moreover, the organisms used for the phosphorus uptake (Polyphosphate Accumulating Organisms) are more efficient under anoxic conditions.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] These microorganisms accumulate large amounts of phosphates in their cells and are settled in the secondary clarifier.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The settled sludge is either disposed of as waste activated sludge or reused in the aeration tank as return activated sludge.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Some sludge must always be returned to the aeration tanks to maintain an adequate population of organisms.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The yield of PAOs (Polyphosphate Accumulating Organisms) is reduced between 70 and 80% under aerobic conditions.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Even though the phosphorus can be removed upstream of the aeration tank by chemical precipitation (adding metal ions such as: calcium, aluminum or iron), the biological phosphorus removal is more economic due to the saving of chemicals.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The process involves air or oxygen being introduced into a mixture of screened, and primary treated sewage or industrial wastewater (wastewater) combined with organisms to develop a biological floc which reduces the organic content of the sewage.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] This material, which in healthy sludge is a brown floc, is largely composed of Saprotrophic bacteria but also has an important protozoan flora component mainly composed of amoebae, Spirotrichs, Peritrichs including Vorticellids and a range of other filter-feeding species.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Other important constituents include motile and sedentary Rotifers.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] This material is often described as sewage fungus but true fungal communities are relatively uncommon.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The combination of wastewater and biological mass is commonly known as *mixed liquor*.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In all activated sludge plants, once the wastewater has received sufficient treatment, excess mixed liquor is discharged into settling tanks and the treated supernatant is run off to undergo further treatment before discharge.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Part of the settled material, the sludge, is returned to the head of the aeration system to re-seed the new wastewater entering the tank.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] This fraction of the floc is called *return activated sludge* (R.A.S.).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The space required for a sewage treatment plant can be reduced by using a membrane bioreactor to remove some wastewater from the mixed liquor prior to treatment.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] This results in a more concentrated waste product that can then be treated using the activated sludge process.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Many sewage treatment plants use axial flow pumps to transfer nitrified mixed liquor from the aeration zone to the anoxic zone for denitrification.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] These pumps are often referred to as internal mixed liquor recycle pumps (IMLR pumps).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The raw sewage, the RAS, and the nitrified mixed liquor are mixed by submersible mixers in the anoxic zones in order to achieve denitrification.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Activated sludge is also the name given to the active biological material produced by activated sludge plants.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Excess sludge is called "surplus activated sludge" or "waste activated sludge" and is removed from the treatment process to keep "food to biomass" (F/M) ratio in balance (where biomass refers to the activated sludge).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] This sewage sludge is usually mixed with primary sludge from the primary clarifiers and undergoes further sludge treatment for example by anaerobic digestion, followed by thickening, dewatering, composting and land application.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The amount of sewage sludge produced from the activated sludge process is directly proportional to the amount of wastewater treated.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The total sludge production consists of the sum of primary sludge from the primary sedimentation tanks as well as waste activated sludge from the bioreactors.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The activated sludge process produces about 70–100 grams per cubic metre (1.9–2.7 oz/cu yd) of waste activated sludge (that is grams of dry solids produced per cubic metre of wastewater treated).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] 80 grams per cubic metre (2.2 oz/cu yd) is regarded as being typical.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In addition, about 110–170 grams per cubic metre (3.0–4.6 oz/cu yd) of primary sludge is produced in the primary sedimentation tanks which most - but not all - of the activated sludge process configurations use.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In the reactor/aerator and clarifier system, the sludge blanket is measured from the bottom of the clarifier to the level of settled solids in the clarifier's water column; this, in large plants, can be done up to three times a day.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The SVI is the volume of settled sludge occupied by a given mass of dry sludge solids.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] It is calculated by dividing the volume of settled sludge in a mixed liquor sample, measured in milliliters per liter of sample (after 30 minutes of settling), by the MLSS (Mixed Liquor Suspended Solids), measured in grams per liter.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The MCRT is the total mass (in kilograms or pounds) of mixed liquor suspended solids in the aerator and clarifier divided by the mass flow rate (in kilograms/pounds per day) of mixed liquor suspended solids leaving as WAS and final effluent.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The F/M is the ratio of food fed to the microorganisms each day to the mass of microorganisms held under aeration.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Specifically, it is the amount of BOD fed to the aerator (in kilograms/pounds per day) divided by the amount (in kilograms or pounds) of Mixed Liquor Volatile Suspended Solids (MLVSS) under aeration.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Note: Some references use MLSS (Mixed Liquor Suspended Solids) for expedience, but MLVSS is considered more accurate for the measure of microorganisms.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Again, due to expedience, COD is generally used, in lieu of BOD, as BOD takes five days for results.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] To ensure good bacterial settlement and to avoid sedimentation problems caused by filamentous bacteria, plants using atmospheric air as an oxygen source should maintain a dissolved oxygen (DO) level of about 2 mg/L in the aeration tank.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In pure oxygen systems, DO levels are usually in the range of 4 to 10 mg/L.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Operators should monitor the tank for low DO bacteria, such as S. natans, type 1701 and H. hydrossis, which indicate low DO conditions by elevated effluent turbidity and dark activated sludge with foul odours.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Many plants have on-line monitoring equipment that continuously measures and records DO levels at specific points within the aeration tank.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] These on-line analysers send data to the SCADA system and allow automatic control of the aeration system to maintain a predetermined DO level.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Whether generated automatically or taken manually, regular monitoring is necessary to favour organisms that settle well rather than filaments.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] However, operating the aeration system involves finding a balance between sufficient oxygen for proper treatment and the energy cost, which represents approximately 90% of the total treatment cost.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Based on these control methods, the amount of settled solids in the mixed liquor can be varied by wasting activated sludge (WAS) or returning activated sludge (RAS).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The returning activated sludge is designed to recycle a portion of the activated sludge from the secondary clarifier back to the aeration tank.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] It usually includes a pump that draws the portion back.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The RAS line is designed considering the potential for clogging, settling, and other relatable issues that manage to impact the flow of the activated sludge back to the aeration tank.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] This line must handle the required flow of the plant and has to be designed to minimize the risk of solids settling or accumulating.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Ammonium can have a toxic effect on aquatic organisms.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Nitrification also takes place in bodies of water, which leads to oxygen depletion.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Furthermore, nitrate and ammonium are eutrophying (fertilizing) nutrients that can impair water bodies.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] For these reasons, nitrification and, in many cases, nitrogen removal is necessary.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] a) Nitrification: Oxidation of ammonium nitrogen and organically bound nitrogen to nitrate.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Nitrification is very sensitive to inhibitors and can lead to a pH value in poorly buffered water.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Nitrification is associated with the production of acid (H+).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] This puts a strain on the buffering capacity of the water or a pH value shift may occur, which impairs the process.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] b) Denitrification: Reduction of nitrate nitrogen to molecular nitrogen, which escapes from the wastewater into the atmosphere.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] This step can be carried out by microorganisms commonly found in sewage treatment plants.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] However, these only use the nitrate as an electron acceptor if no dissolved oxygen is present.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In order for denitrification to take place in the activated sludge process, an electron source, a reductant, must therefore also be present that can reduce sufficient nitrate to N2.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] If there is too little substrate in the raw wastewater, this can be added artificially.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In addition, denitrification corrects the change in H+ concentration (pH value shift) that occurs during nitrification.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] This is particularly important for poorly buffered water.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Nitrification and denitrification are in considerable contradiction with regard to the required environmental conditions.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Denitrification only takes place in the absence of dissolved oxygen and with a sufficient supply of oxidizable substances.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] There are a variety of types of activated sludge plants.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] There are a wide range of types of package plants, often serving small communities or industrial plants that may use hybrid treatment processes often involving the use of aerobic sludge to treat the incoming sewage.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In such plants the primary settlement stage of treatment may be omitted.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In these plants, a biotic floc is created which provides the required substrate.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Package plants are designed and fabricated by specialty engineering firms in dimensions that allow for their transportation to the job site in public highways, typically width and height of 3.7 by 3.7 metres (12 ft × 12 ft).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Length varies with capacity with larger plants being fabricated in pieces and welded on site.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Steel is preferred over synthetic materials (e.g., plastic) for its durability.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Package plants are commonly variants of extended aeration, to promote the "fit and forget" approach required for small communities without dedicated operational staff.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] There are various standards to assist with their design.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] To use less space, treat difficult waste, and intermittent flows, a number of designs of hybrid treatment plants have been produced.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Such plants often combine at least two stages of the three main treatment stages into one combined stage.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In the UK, where a large number of wastewater treatment plants serve small populations, package plants are a viable alternative to building a large structure for each process stage.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In the US, package plants are typically used in rural areas, highway rest stops and trailer parks.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Package plants may be referred to as *high charged* or *low charged*.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] This refers to the way the biological load is processed.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In high charged systems, the biological stage is presented with a high organic load and the combined floc and organic material is then oxygenated for a few hours before being charged again with a new load.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In the low charged system the biological stage contains a low organic load and is combined with flocculate for longer times.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In some areas, where more land is available, sewage is treated in large round or oval ditches with one or more horizontal aerators typically called brush or disc aerators which drive the mixed liquor around the ditch and provide aeration.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] These are oxidation ditches, often referred to by manufacturer's trade names such as Pasveer, Orbal, or Carrousel.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] They have the advantage that they are relatively easy to maintain and are resilient to shock loads that often occur in smaller communities (i.e. at breakfast time and in the evening).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Oxidation ditches are installed commonly as 'fit & forget' technology, with typical design parameters of a hydraulic retention time of 24 – 48 hours, and a sludge age of 12 – 20 days.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] This compares with nitrifying activated sludge plants having a retention time of 8 hours, and a sludge age of 8 – 12 days.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Where land is in short supply sewage may be treated by injection of oxygen into a pressured return sludge stream which is injected into the base of a deep columnar tank buried in the ground.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Such shafts may be up to 100 metres (330 ft) deep and are filled with sewage liquor.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] As the sewage rises the oxygen forced into solution by the pressure at the base of the shaft breaks out as molecular oxygen providing a highly efficient source of oxygen for the activated sludge biota.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The rising oxygen and injected return sludge provide the physical mechanism for mixing of the sewage and sludge.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Mixed sludge and sewage is decanted at the surface and separated into supernatant and sludge components.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The efficiency of deep shaft treatment can be high.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Surface aerators are commonly quoted as having an aeration efficiency of 0.5–1.5 kg O2/kWh (1.1–3.3 lb O2/kWh), diffused aeration as 1.5–2.5 kg O2/kWh (3.3–5.5 lb O2/kWh).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] However, the costs of construction are high.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Deep Shaft has seen the greatest uptake in Japan, because of the land area issues.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Deep Shaft was developed by ICI, as a spin-off from their Pruteen process.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] DeepShaft is a patented, licensed, process.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The licensee has changed several times and currently (2015) Noram Engineering sells it.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Most biological oxidation processes for treating industrial wastewaters have in common the use of oxygen (or air) and microbial action.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Surface-aerated basins achieve 80 to 90% removal of BOD with retention times of 1 to 10 days.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The basins may range in depth from 1.5 to 5.0 metres (4.9 to 16.4 ft) and utilize motor-driven aerators floating on the surface of the wastewater.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In an aerated basin system, the aerators provide two functions: they transfer air into the basins required by the biological oxidation reactions, and they provide the mixing required for dispersing the air and for contacting the reactants (that is, oxygen, wastewater and microbes).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Typically, the floating surface aerators are rated to deliver the amount of air equivalent to 1.8 to 2.7 kilograms O2/kWh (4.0 to 6.0 lb O2/kWh).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] However, they do not provide as good mixing as is normally achieved in activated sludge systems and therefore aerated basins do not achieve the same performance level as activated sludge units.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Biological oxidation processes are sensitive to temperature and, between 0 and 40 °C (32 and 104 °F), the rate of biological reactions increase with temperature.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Most surface aerated vessels operate at between 4 and 32 °C (39 and 90 °F).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Sequencing batch reactors (SBRs) treat wastewater in batches within the same vessel.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] This means that the bioreactor and final clarifier are not separated in space but in a timed sequence.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The installation consists of at least two identically equipped tanks with a common inlet, which can be alternated between them.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] While one tank is in settle/decant mode the other is aerating and filling.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Sewage liquor is run into deep tanks with diffuser grid aeration systems that are attached to the floor.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] These are like the diffused airstone used in tropical fish tanks but on a much larger scale.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Air is pumped through the blocks and the curtain of bubbles formed both oxygenates the liquor and also provides the necessary mixing action.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Where capacity is limited or the sewage is unusually strong or difficult to treat, oxygen may be used instead of air.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Typically, the air is generated by some type of air blower.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Vertically mounted tubes of up to 1-metre (3.3 ft) diameter extending from just above the base of a deep concrete tank to just below the surface of the sewage liquor.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] A typical shaft might be 10 metres (33 ft) high.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] At the surface end, the tube is formed into a cone with helical vanes attached to the inner surface.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] When the tube is rotated, the vanes spin liquor up and out of the cones drawing new sewage liquor from the base of the tank.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In many works, each cone is located in a separate cell that can be isolated from the remaining cells if required for maintenance.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Some works may have two cones to a cell and some large works may have 4 cones per cell.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Pure oxygen activated sludge aeration systems are sealed-tank reactor vessels with surface aerator type impellers mounted within the tanks at the oxygen carbon liquor surface interface.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The amount of oxygen entrainment, or DO (Dissolved Oxygen), can be controlled by a weir adjusted level control, and a vent gas oxygen controlled oxygen feed valve.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Oxygen is generated on site by cryogenic distillation of air, pressure swing adsorption, or other methods.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] These systems are used where wastewater plant space is at a premium and high sewage throughput is required as high energy costs are involved in purifying oxygen.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] A new development of the activated sludge process is the Nereda process which produces a granular sludge that settles very well (the sludge volume index is reduced from 200–300 to 40 millilitres per gram (192–288 to 38 US fl oz/oz)).
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] A new process reactor system is created to take advantage of this quick settling sludge and is integrated into the aeration tank instead of having a separate unit outside.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] As of 2015, about 30 Nereda wastewater treatment plants worldwide were operational, under construction or under design, varying in size from 5,000 up to 858,000 person equivalent.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The discharge of toxic industrial pollution to treatment plants designed primarily to treat domestic sewage can create process upsets.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The activated sludge process is an example for a more high-tech, energy intensive or "mechanized" process that is relatively expensive compared to some other wastewater treatment systems.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] It can provide a very high level of treatment.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Activated sludge plants are wholly dependent on an electrical supply to power the aerators to transfer settled solids back to the aeration tank inlet, and in many cases to pump waste sludge and final effluent.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In some works untreated sewage is lifted by pumps to the head-works to provide sufficient fall through the works to enable a satisfactory discharge head for the final effluent.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Alternative technologies such as trickling filter treatment requires much less power and can operate on gravity alone.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] The activated sludge process was discovered in 1913 in the United Kingdom by two engineers, Edward Ardern and W.T.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Lockett, who were conducting research for the Manchester Corporation Rivers Department at Davyhulme Sewage Works.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In 1912, Gilbert Fowler, a scientist at the University of Manchester, observed experiments being conducted at the Lawrence Experiment Station at Massachusetts involving the aeration of sewage in a bottle that had been coated with algae.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Fowler's engineering colleagues, Ardern and Lockett, experimented on treating sewage in a draw-and-fill reactor, which produced a highly treated effluent.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] They aerated the waste-water continuously for about a month and were able to achieve a complete nitrification of the sample material.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Believing that the sludge had been activated (in a similar manner to activated carbon) the process was named *activated sludge*.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] Their results were published in their seminal 1914 paper, and the first full-scale continuous-flow system was installed at Worcester two years later.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] In the aftermath of the First World War the new treatment method spread rapidly, especially to the US, Denmark, Germany and Canada.
[src:biomass/activated-sludge] By the late 1930s, the activated sludge treatment became a well-known biological wastewater treatment process in those countries where sewer systems and sewage treatment plants were common.
[src:biomass/animal] The animal kingdom is divided into five major clades, namely Porifera, Ctenophora, Placozoa, Cnidaria and Bilateria.
[src:biomass/animal] The much smaller basal phylum Xenacoelomorpha have an uncertain position within Bilateria.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals first appeared in the fossil record in the late Cryogenian period and diversified in the subsequent Ediacaran period in what is known as the Avalon explosion.
[src:biomass/animal] Nearly all modern animal phyla first appeared in the fossil record as marine species during the Cambrian explosion, which began around 539 million years ago (Mya), and most classes during the Ordovician radiation 485.4 Mya.
[src:biomass/animal] Common to all living animals, 6,331 groups of genes have been identified that may have arisen from a single common ancestor that lived about 650 Mya during the Cryogenian period.
[src:biomass/animal] Historically, Aristotle divided animals into those with blood and those without.
[src:biomass/animal] Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical biological classification for animals in 1758 with his *Systema Naturae*, which Jean-Baptiste Lamarck expanded into 14 phyla by 1809.
[src:biomass/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into the multicellular **Metazoa** (now synonymous with Animalia) and the Protozoa, single-celled organisms no longer considered animals.
[src:biomass/animal] In modern times, the biological classification of animals relies on advanced techniques, such as molecular phylogenetics, which are effective at demonstrating the evolutionary relationships between taxa.
[src:biomass/animal] Humans make use of many other animal species for food (including meat, eggs, and dairy products), for materials (such as leather, fur, and wool), as pets and as working animals for transportation, and services.
[src:biomass/animal] Dogs, the first domesticated animal, have been used in hunting, in security and in warfare, as have horses, pigeons and birds of prey; while other terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sports, trophies or profits.
[src:biomass/animal] Non-human animals are also an important cultural element of human evolution, having appeared in cave arts and totems since the earliest times, and are frequently featured in mythology, religion, arts, literature, heraldry, politics, and sports.
[src:biomass/animal] The word *animal* comes from the Latin noun *animal* of the same meaning, which is itself derived from Latin *animalis* 'having breath or soul'.
[src:biomass/animal] The biological definition includes all members of the kingdom Animalia.
[src:biomass/animal] In colloquial usage, the term *animal* is often used to refer only to nonhuman animals.
[src:biomass/animal] The term *metazoa* is derived from Ancient Greek μετα *meta* 'after' (in biology, the prefix *meta-* stands for 'later') and ζῷᾰ *zōia* 'animals', plural of ζῷον *zōion* 'animal'.
[src:biomass/animal] A **metazoan** is any member of the group *Metazoa*.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals have several characteristics that they share with other living things.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals are eukaryotic, multicellular, and aerobic, as are plants and fungi.
[src:biomass/animal] Unlike plants and algae, which produce their own food, animals cannot produce their own food, a feature they share with fungi.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals ingest organic material and digest it internally.
[src:biomass/animal] Typically, there is an internal digestive chamber with either one opening (in Ctenophora, Cnidaria, and flatworms) or two openings (in most bilaterians).
[src:biomass/animal] Animal development is controlled by Hox genes, which signal the times and places to develop structures such as body segments and limbs.
[src:biomass/animal] During development, the animal extracellular matrix forms a relatively flexible framework upon which cells can move about and be reorganised into specialised tissues and organs, making the formation of complex structures possible, and allowing cells to be differentiated.
[src:biomass/animal] The extracellular matrix may be calcified, forming structures such as shells, bones, and spicules.
[src:biomass/animal] In contrast, the cells of other multicellular organisms (primarily algae, plants, and fungi) are held in place by cell walls, and so develop by progressive growth.
[src:biomass/animal] Nearly all animals make use of some form of sexual reproduction.
[src:biomass/animal] They produce haploid gametes by meiosis; the smaller, motile gametes are spermatozoa and the larger, non-motile gametes are ova.
[src:biomass/animal] These fuse to form zygotes, which develop via mitosis into a hollow sphere, called a blastula.
[src:biomass/animal] In sponges, blastula larvae swim to a new location, attach to the seabed, and develop into a new sponge.
[src:biomass/animal] In most other groups, the blastula undergoes more complicated rearrangement.
[src:biomass/animal] It first invaginates to form a gastrula with a digestive chamber and two separate germ layers, an external ectoderm and an internal endoderm.
[src:biomass/animal] In most cases, a third germ layer, the mesoderm, also develops between them.
[src:biomass/animal] These germ layers then differentiate to form tissues and organs.
[src:biomass/animal] Repeated instances of mating with a close relative during sexual reproduction generally leads to inbreeding depression within a population due to the increased prevalence of harmful recessive traits.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals have evolved numerous mechanisms for avoiding close inbreeding.
[src:biomass/animal] Some animals are capable of asexual reproduction, which often results in a genetic clone of the parent.
[src:biomass/animal] This may take place through fragmentation; budding, such as in *Hydra* and other cnidarians; or parthenogenesis, where fertile eggs are produced without mating, such as in aphids.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals are categorised into ecological groups depending on their trophic levels and how they consume organic material.
[src:biomass/animal] Such groupings include carnivores (further divided into subcategories such as piscivores, insectivores, ovivores, etc.), herbivores (subcategorised into folivores, graminivores, frugivores, granivores, nectarivores, algivores, etc.), omnivores, fungivores, scavengers/detritivores, and parasites.
[src:biomass/animal] Interactions between animals of each biome form complex food webs within that ecosystem.
[src:biomass/animal] In carnivorous or omnivorous species, predation is a consumer–resource interaction where the predator feeds on another organism, its prey, who often evolves anti-predator adaptations to avoid being fed upon.
[src:biomass/animal] Selective pressures imposed on one another lead to an evolutionary arms race between predator and prey, resulting in various antagonistic/competitive coevolutions.
[src:biomass/animal] Almost all multicellular predators are animals.
[src:biomass/animal] Some consumers use multiple methods; for example, in parasitoid wasps, the larvae feed on the hosts' living tissues, killing them in the process, but the adults primarily consume nectar from flowers.
[src:biomass/animal] Other animals may have very specific feeding behaviours, such as hawksbill sea turtles which mainly eat sponges.
[src:biomass/animal] Most animals rely on biomass and bioenergy produced by plants and phytoplanktons (collectively called producers) through photosynthesis.
[src:biomass/animal] Herbivores, as primary consumers, eat the plant material directly to digest and absorb the nutrients, while carnivores and other animals on higher trophic levels indirectly acquire the nutrients by eating the herbivores or other animals that have eaten the herbivores.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals oxidise carbohydrates, lipids, proteins and other biomolecules in cellular respiration, which allows the animal to grow and to sustain basal metabolism and fuel other biological processes such as locomotion.
[src:biomass/animal] Some benthic animals living close to hydrothermal vents and cold seeps on the dark sea floor consume organic matter produced through chemosynthesis (via oxidising inorganic compounds such as hydrogen sulfide) by archaea and bacteria.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals originated in the ocean; all extant animal phyla, except for Micrognathozoa and Onychophora, feature at least some marine species.
[src:biomass/animal] However, several lineages of arthropods begun to colonise land around the same time as land plants, between 510 and 471 million years ago, during the Late Cambrian or Early Ordovician periods.
[src:biomass/animal] Vertebrates such as the lobe-finned fish *Tiktaalik* started to move on to land in the late Devonian, about 375 million years ago.
[src:biomass/animal] Other notable animal groups that colonized land environments are Mollusca, Platyhelmintha, Annelida, Tardigrada, Onychophora, Rotifera, Nematoda.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals occupy virtually all of earth's habitats and microhabitats, with faunas adapted to salt water, hydrothermal vents, fresh water, hot springs, swamps, forests, pastures, deserts, air, and the interiors of other organisms.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals are however not particularly heat tolerant; very few of them can survive at constant temperatures above 50 °C (122 °F) or in the most extreme cold deserts of continental Antarctica.
[src:biomass/animal] The collective global geomorphic influence of animals on the processes shaping the Earth's surface remains largely understudied, with most studies limited to individual species and well-known exemplars.
[src:biomass/animal] The blue whale (*Balaenoptera musculus*) is the largest animal that has ever lived, weighing up to 190 tonnes and measuring up to 33.6 metres (110 ft) long.
[src:biomass/animal] The largest extant terrestrial animal is the African bush elephant (*Loxodonta africana*), weighing up to 12.25 tonnes and measuring up to 10.67 metres (35.0 ft) long.
[src:biomass/animal] The largest terrestrial animals that ever lived were titanosaur sauropod dinosaurs such as *Argentinosaurus*, which may have weighed as much as 73 tonnes, and *Supersaurus* which may have reached 39 metres.
[src:biomass/animal] Several animals are microscopic; some Myxozoa (obligate parasites within the Cnidaria) never grow larger than 20 μm, and one of the smallest species (*Myxobolus shekel*) is no more than 8.5 μm when fully grown.
[src:biomass/animal] The following table lists estimated numbers of described extant species for the major animal phyla, along with their principal habitats (terrestrial, fresh water, and marine), and free-living or parasitic ways of life.
[src:biomass/animal] Species estimates shown here are based on numbers described scientifically; much larger estimates have been calculated based on various means of prediction, and these can vary wildly.
[src:biomass/animal] For instance, around 25,000–27,000 species of nematodes have been described, while published estimates of the total number of nematode species include 10,000–20,000; 500,000; 10 million; and 100 million.
[src:biomass/animal] Using patterns within the taxonomic hierarchy, the total number of animal species—including those not yet described—was calculated to be about 7.77 million in 2011.
[src:biomass/animal] Evidence of animals is found as long ago as the Cryogenian period.
[src:biomass/animal] 24-Isopropylcholestane (24-ipc) has been found in rocks from roughly 650 million years ago; it is only produced by sponges and pelagophyte algae.
[src:biomass/animal] Its likely origin is from sponges based on molecular clock estimates for the origin of 24-ipc production in both groups.
[src:biomass/animal] Analyses of pelagophyte algae consistently recover a Phanerozoic origin, while analyses of sponges recover a Neoproterozoic origin, consistent with the appearance of 24-ipc in the fossil record.
[src:biomass/animal] The first body fossils of animals appear in the Ediacaran, represented by forms such as *Charnia* and *Spriggina*.
[src:biomass/animal] It had long been doubted whether these fossils truly represented animals, but the discovery of the animal lipid cholesterol in fossils of *Dickinsonia* establishes their nature.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals are thought to have originated under low-oxygen conditions, suggesting that they were capable of living entirely by anaerobic respiration, but as they became specialised for aerobic metabolism they became fully dependent on oxygen in their environments.
[src:biomass/animal] Many animal phyla first appear in the fossil record during the Cambrian explosion, starting about 539 million years ago, in beds such as the Burgess Shale.
[src:biomass/animal] Extant phyla in these rocks include molluscs, brachiopods, onychophorans, tardigrades, arthropods, echinoderms and hemichordates, along with numerous now-extinct forms such as the predatory *Anomalocaris*.
[src:biomass/animal] The apparent suddenness of the event may however be an artefact of the fossil record, rather than showing that all these animals appeared simultaneously.
[src:biomass/animal] That view is supported by the discovery of *Auroralumina attenboroughii*, the earliest known Ediacaran crown-group cnidarian (557–562 mya, some 20 million years before the Cambrian explosion) from Charnwood Forest, England.
[src:biomass/animal] It is thought to be one of the earliest predators, catching small prey with its nematocysts as modern cnidarians do.
[src:biomass/animal] Some palaeontologists have suggested that animals appeared much earlier than the Cambrian explosion, possibly as early as 1 billion years ago.
[src:biomass/animal] Early fossils that might represent animals appear for example in the 665-million-year-old rocks of the Trezona Formation of South Australia.
[src:biomass/animal] These fossils are interpreted as most probably being early sponges.
[src:biomass/animal] Trace fossils such as tracks and burrows found in the Tonian period (from 1 gya) may indicate the presence of triploblastic worm-like animals, roughly as large (about 5 mm wide) and complex as earthworms.
[src:biomass/animal] However, similar tracks are produced by the giant single-celled protist *Gromia sphaerica*, so the Tonian trace fossils may not indicate early animal evolution.
[src:biomass/animal] Around the same time, the layered mats of microorganisms called stromatolites decreased in diversity, perhaps due to grazing by newly evolved animals.
[src:biomass/animal] Objects such as sediment-filled tubes that resemble trace fossils of the burrows of wormlike animals have been found in 1.2 gya rocks in North America, in 1.5 gya rocks in Australia and North America, and in 1.7 gya rocks in Australia.
[src:biomass/animal] Their interpretation as having an animal origin is disputed, as they might be water-escape or other structures.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals are monophyletic, meaning they are derived from a common ancestor.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals are the sister group to the choanoflagellates, with which they form the Choanozoa.
[src:biomass/animal] Ros-Rocher and colleagues (2021) trace the origins of animals to unicellular ancestors, providing the external phylogeny shown in the cladogram.
[src:biomass/animal] Uncertainty of relationships is indicated with dashed lines.
[src:biomass/animal] The animal clade had certainly originated by 650 mya, and may have come into being as much as 800 mya, based on molecular clock evidence for different phyla.
[src:biomass/animal] The relationships at the base of the animal tree have been debated.
[src:biomass/animal] Other than Ctenophora, the Bilateria and Cnidaria are the only groups with symmetry, and other evidence shows they are closely related.
[src:biomass/animal] In addition to sponges, Placozoa has no symmetry and was often considered a "missing link" between protists and multicellular animals.
[src:biomass/animal] The presence of hox genes in Placozoa shows that they were once more complex.
[src:biomass/animal] The Porifera (sponges) have long been assumed to be sister to the rest of the animals, but there is evidence that the Ctenophora may be in that position.
[src:biomass/animal] Molecular phylogenetics has supported both the sponge-sister and ctenophore-sister hypotheses.
[src:biomass/animal] Sponges are physically very distinct from other animals, and were long thought to have diverged first, representing the oldest animal phylum and forming a sister clade to all other animals.
[src:biomass/animal] Despite their morphological dissimilarity with all other animals, genetic evidence suggests sponges may be more closely related to other animals than the comb jellies are.
[src:biomass/animal] Sponges lack the complex organisation found in most other animal phyla; their cells are differentiated, but in most cases not organised into distinct tissues, unlike all other animals.
[src:biomass/animal] Sponges are almost entirely sessile in their adult stage.
[src:biomass/animal] Sponges lack a digestive, circulatory, respiratory, or excretory system.
[src:biomass/animal] Instead, they rely on the flow of water through their bodies to perform these functions.
[src:biomass/animal] Many have adapted a hollow structure to facilitate the flow of water through their bodies.
[src:biomass/animal] They typically feed by drawing in water through pores, filtering out small particles of food.
[src:biomass/animal] They absorb oxygen dissolved in water, and they release carbon dioxide and nitrogenous waste into water that flows through them.
[src:biomass/animal] Sponges can reproduce sexually and asexually.
[src:biomass/animal] Asexual reproduction happens through a variety of mechanisms including by fragmentation, where a piece of the sponge splits off and reestablishes somewhere else.
[src:biomass/animal] For sexual reproduction, most sponges are hermaphrodites, they produce both egg and sperm cells.
[src:biomass/animal] Comb jellies, members of Ctenophora, are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:biomass/animal] Ctenophora have distinct tissues, but these are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:biomass/animal] They move using large arrays of cilia, called swimming plates.
[src:biomass/animal] They have are unique in having colloblasts, structures on their tentacles that help them catch prey.
[src:biomass/animal] They have nerve cells, but lack a brain or central nervous system.
[src:biomass/animal] Instead their nerves are arranged into a nerve net.
[src:biomass/animal] Their nerves are very different from those of other animals, and evidence suggests that their nerves developed independently of the nerves of other animals.
[src:biomass/animal] Like Ctenophora, Cnidaria are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:biomass/animal] They also have distinct tissues that are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:biomass/animal] Members of the group Anthozoa, such as sea anemones, coral, and sea pens only are sessile polyps.
[src:biomass/animal] Most members of Medusozoa, including jellyfish and most hydrozoans, have a polyp form as well, but also have a motile medusae stage.
[src:biomass/animal] The medusae stage are commonly known as jellyfish.
[src:biomass/animal] Cnidaria are diploblastic, having only two main germ layers, ectoderm and endoderm.
[src:biomass/animal] The tiny placozoans have no permanent digestive chamber and no symmetry; they superficially resemble amoebae.
[src:biomass/animal] Their phylogeny is poorly defined, and under active research.
[src:biomass/animal] The remaining animals, the great majority—comprising some 29 phyla and over a million species—form the Bilateria clade, which have a bilaterally symmetric body plan.
[src:biomass/animal] The Bilateria are triploblastic, with three well-developed germ layers, and their tissues form distinct organs.
[src:biomass/animal] The digestive chamber has two openings, a mouth and an anus, and in the Nephrozoa there is an internal body cavity, a coelom or pseudocoelom.
[src:biomass/animal] These animals have a head end (anterior) and a tail end (posterior), a back (dorsal) surface and a belly (ventral) surface, and a left and a right side.
[src:biomass/animal] A modern consensus phylogenetic tree for the Bilateria is shown below.
[src:biomass/animal] Having a front end means that this part of the body encounters stimuli, such as food, favouring cephalisation, the development of a head with sense organs and a mouth.
[src:biomass/animal] Many bilaterians have a combination of circular muscles that constrict the body, making it longer, and an opposing set of longitudinal muscles, that shorten the body; these enable soft-bodied animals with a hydrostatic skeleton to move by peristalsis.
[src:biomass/animal] They also have a gut that extends through the basically cylindrical body from mouth to anus.
[src:biomass/animal] Many bilaterian phyla have primary larvae which swim with cilia and have an apical organ containing sensory cells.
[src:biomass/animal] However, over evolutionary time, descendant spaces have evolved which have lost one or more of each of these characteristics.
[src:biomass/animal] For example, adult echinoderms are radially symmetric (unlike their larvae), while some parasitic worms have extremely simplified body structures.
[src:biomass/animal] Genetic studies have considerably changed zoologists' understanding of the relationships within the Bilateria.
[src:biomass/animal] Most appear to belong to two major lineages, the protostomes and the deuterostomes.
[src:biomass/animal] It is often suggested that the basalmost bilaterians are the Xenacoelomorpha, with all other bilaterians belonging to the subclade Nephrozoa.
[src:biomass/animal] However, this suggestion has been contested, with other studies finding that xenacoelomorphs are more closely related to Ambulacraria than to other bilaterians.
[src:biomass/animal] Protostomes and deuterostomes differ in several ways.
[src:biomass/animal] Early in development, deuterostome embryos undergo radial cleavage during cell division, while many protostomes (the Spiralia) undergo spiral cleavage.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals from both groups possess a complete digestive tract, but in protostomes the first opening of the embryonic gut develops into the mouth, and the anus forms secondarily.
[src:biomass/animal] In deuterostomes, the anus forms first while the mouth develops secondarily.
[src:biomass/animal] Most protostomes have schizocoelous development, where cells simply fill in the interior of the gastrula to form the mesoderm.
[src:biomass/animal] In deuterostomes, the mesoderm forms by enterocoelic pouching, through invagination of the endoderm.
[src:biomass/animal] The main deuterostome taxa are the Ambulacraria and the Chordata.
[src:biomass/animal] Ambulacraria are exclusively marine and include acorn worms, starfish, sea urchins, and sea cucumbers.
[src:biomass/animal] The chordates are dominated by the vertebrates (animals with backbones), which consist of fishes, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.
[src:biomass/animal] The protostomes include the Ecdysozoa, named after their shared trait of ecdysis, growth by moulting, Among the largest ecdysozoan phyla are the arthropods and the nematodes.
[src:biomass/animal] The rest of the protostomes are in the Spiralia, named for their pattern of developing by spiral cleavage in the early embryo.
[src:biomass/animal] Major spiralian phyla include the annelids and molluscs.
[src:biomass/animal] In the classical era, Aristotle divided animals, based on his own observations, into those with blood (roughly, the vertebrates) and those without.
[src:biomass/animal] In 1758, Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical classification in his *Systema Naturae*.
[src:biomass/animal] In his original scheme, the animals were one of three kingdoms, divided into the classes of Vermes, Insecta, Pisces, Amphibia, Aves, and Mammalia.
[src:biomass/animal] Since then, the last four have all been subsumed into a single phylum, the Chordata, while his Insecta (which included the crustaceans and arachnids) and Vermes have been renamed or broken up.
[src:biomass/animal] The process was begun in 1793 by Jean-Baptiste de Lamarck, who called the Vermes *une espèce de chaos* ('a chaotic mess') and split the group into three new phyla: worms, echinoderms, and polyps (which contained corals and jellyfish).
[src:biomass/animal] By 1809, in his *Philosophie Zoologique*, Lamarck had created nine phyla apart from vertebrates (where he still had four phyla: mammals, birds, reptiles, and fish) and molluscs, namely cirripedes, annelids, crustaceans, arachnids, insects, worms, radiates, polyps, and infusorians.
[src:biomass/animal] This division into four was followed by the embryologist Karl Ernst von Baer in 1828, the zoologist Louis Agassiz in 1857, and the comparative anatomist Richard Owen in 1860.
[src:biomass/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into two subkingdoms: Metazoa (multicellular animals, with five phyla: coelenterates, echinoderms, articulates, molluscs, and vertebrates) and Protozoa (single-celled animals), including a sixth animal phylum, sponges.
[src:biomass/animal] The protozoa were later moved to the former kingdom Protista, leaving only the Metazoa as a synonym of Animalia.
[src:biomass/animal] The human population exploits a large number of other animal species for food, both of domesticated livestock species in animal husbandry and, mainly at sea, by hunting wild species.
[src:biomass/animal] Marine fish of many species are caught commercially for food.
[src:biomass/animal] A smaller number of species are farmed commercially.
[src:biomass/animal] Humans and their livestock make up more than 90% of the biomass of all terrestrial vertebrates, and almost as much as all insects combined.
[src:biomass/animal] Invertebrates including cephalopods, crustaceans, insects—principally bees and silkworms—and bivalve or gastropod molluscs are hunted or farmed for food, fibres.
[src:biomass/animal] Chickens, cattle, sheep, pigs, and other animals are raised as livestock for meat across the world.
[src:biomass/animal] Animal fibres such as wool and silk are used to make textiles, while animal sinews have been used as lashings and bindings, and leather is widely used to make shoes and other items.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals have been hunted and farmed for their fur to make items such as coats and hats.
[src:biomass/animal] Dyestuffs including carmine (cochineal), shellac, and kermes have been made from the bodies of insects.
[src:biomass/animal] Working animals including cattle and horses have been used for work and transport from the first days of agriculture.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals such as the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* serve a major role in science as experimental models.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals have been used to create vaccines since their discovery in the 18th century.
[src:biomass/animal] Some medicines such as the cancer drug trabectedin are based on toxins or other molecules of animal origin.
[src:biomass/animal] People have used hunting dogs to help chase down and retrieve animals, and birds of prey to catch birds and mammals, while tethered cormorants have been used to catch fish.
[src:biomass/animal] Poison dart frogs have been used to poison the tips of blowpipe darts.
[src:biomass/animal] A wide variety of animals are kept as pets, from invertebrates such as tarantulas, octopuses, and praying mantises, reptiles such as snakes and chameleons, and birds including canaries, parakeets, and parrots all finding a place.
[src:biomass/animal] However, the most kept pet species are mammals, namely dogs, cats, and rabbits.
[src:biomass/animal] There is a tension between the role of animals as companions to humans, and their existence as individuals with rights of their own.
[src:biomass/animal] A wide variety of terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sport.
[src:biomass/animal] The signs of the Western and Chinese zodiacs are based on animals.
[src:biomass/animal] In China and Japan, the butterfly has been seen as the personification of a person's soul, and in classical representation the butterfly is also the symbol of the soul.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals have been the subjects of art from the earliest times, both historical, as in ancient Egypt, and prehistoric, as in the cave paintings at Lascaux.
[src:biomass/animal] Major animal paintings include Albrecht Dürer's 1515 *The Rhinoceros*, and George Stubbs's c.
[src:biomass/animal] Insects, birds and mammals play roles in literature and film, such as in giant bug movies.
[src:biomass/animal] Animals including insects and mammals feature in mythology and religion.
[src:biomass/animal] The scarab beetle was sacred in ancient Egypt, and the cow is sacred in Hinduism.
[src:biomass/animal] Among other mammals, deer, horses, lions, bats, bears, and wolves are the subjects of myths and worship.
[src:biomass/arcology] An **arcology** or **vertical city** is a hypothetical mixed-use megastructure featuring high population density with the goal of autarky from the outside environment.
[src:biomass/arcology] The term was coined in 1969 by architect Paolo Soleri as a portmanteau of "architecture" and "ecology." Soleri believed that a completed arcology would provide space for a variety of residential, commercial, and agricultural facilities while minimizing individual human environmental impact.
[src:biomass/arcology] The concept has been promoted by various science fiction writers.
[src:biomass/arcology] Larry Niven and Jerry Pournelle provided a detailed description of an arcology in their 1981 novel *Oath of Fealty*.
[src:biomass/arcology] William Gibson popularized the term in his seminal 1984 cyberpunk novel *Neuromancer*, where each corporation has its own self-contained city known as an arcology.
[src:biomass/arcology] More recently, authors such as Peter Hamilton in *Neutronium Alchemist* and Paolo Bacigalupi in *The Water Knife* explicitly used arcologies as part of their scenarios.
[src:biomass/arcology] They are often portrayed as self-contained or economically self-sufficient.
[src:biomass/arcology] An arcology is distinguished from a merely large building in that it is designed to lessen the impact of human habitation on any given ecosystem.
[src:biomass/arcology] It could be self-sustainable, employing all or most of its own available resources for a comfortable life: power, climate control, food production, air and water conservation and purification, sewage treatment, etc.
[src:biomass/arcology] An arcology is designed to make it possible to supply those items for a large population.
[src:biomass/arcology] An arcology would supply and maintain its own municipal or urban infrastructures in order to operate and connect with other urban environments apart from its own.
[src:biomass/arcology] Arcologies were proposed in order to reduce human impact on natural resources.
[src:biomass/arcology] Arcology designs might apply conventional building and civil engineering techniques in very large, but practical projects in order to achieve pedestrian economies of scale that have proven, post-automobile, to be difficult to achieve in other ways.
[src:biomass/arcology] Frank Lloyd Wright proposed an early version called Broadacre City although, in contrast to an arcology, his idea is comparatively two-dimensional and depends on a road network.
[src:biomass/arcology] Wright's plan described transportation, agriculture, and commerce systems that would support an economy.
[src:biomass/arcology] Critics said that Wright's solution failed to account for population growth, and assumed a more rigid democracy than the US actually has.
[src:biomass/arcology] Buckminster Fuller proposed the Old Man River's City project, a domed city with a capacity of 125,000, as a solution to the housing problems in East St.
[src:biomass/arcology] Paolo Soleri proposed later solutions, and coined the term "arcology".
[src:biomass/arcology] Soleri describes ways of compacting city structures in three dimensions to combat two-dimensional urban sprawl, to economize on transportation and other energy uses.
[src:biomass/arcology] Like Wright, Soleri proposed changes in transportation, agriculture, and commerce.
[src:biomass/arcology] Soleri explored reductions in resource consumption and duplication, land reclamation; he also proposed to eliminate most private transportation.
[src:biomass/arcology] He advocated for greater "frugality" and favored greater use of shared social resources, including public transit (and public libraries).
[src:biomass/arcology] Arcosanti is an experimental "arcology prototype", a demonstration project under construction in central Arizona since 1970.
[src:biomass/arcology] Designed by Paolo Soleri, its primary purpose is to demonstrate Soleri's personal designs, his application of principles of arcology to create a pedestrian-friendly urban form.
[src:biomass/arcology] Many cities in the world have proposed projects adhering to the design principles of the arcology concept, like Tokyo, and Dongtan near Shanghai.
[src:biomass/arcology] The Dongtan project may have collapsed, and it failed to open for the Shanghai World Expo in 2010.
[src:biomass/arcology] The Ihme-Zentrum in Hanover was an attempt to build a "city within a city".
[src:biomass/arcology] McMurdo Station of the United States Antarctic Program and other scientific research stations on Antarctica resemble the popular conception of an arcology as a technologically advanced, relatively self-sufficient human community.
[src:biomass/arcology] The Antarctic research base provides living and entertainment amenities for roughly 3,000 staff who visit each year.
[src:biomass/arcology] Its remoteness and the measures needed to protect its population from the harsh environment give it an insular character.
[src:biomass/arcology] The station is not self-sufficient: The U.S. military delivers 30,000,000 liters (8,000,000 US gal) of fuel and 5 kilotonnes (11 million pounds) of supplies and equipment yearly through its Operation Deep Freeze resupply effort, but it is isolated from conventional support networks.
[src:biomass/arcology] Under international treaty, it must avoid damage to the surrounding ecosystem.
[src:biomass/arcology] Begich Towers operates like a small-scale arcology encompassing nearly all of the population of Whittier, Alaska.
[src:biomass/arcology] The building contains residential housing as well as a police station, grocery, and municipal offices.
[src:biomass/arcology] The Line was planned as a 170-kilometre (110 mi) long and 200-metre (660 ft) wide linear smart city in Saudi Arabia in Neom, Tabuk Province, designed to have no cars, streets or greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:biomass/arcology] The Line is planned to be the first development in Neom, a $500 billion project.
[src:biomass/arcology] The city's plans anticipated a population of 9 million.
[src:biomass/arcology] Excavation work had started along the entire length of the project by October 2022.
[src:biomass/arcology] However, the project was scaled down in 2024 to 2.4 kilometres (1.5 mi) long, housing 300,000 people.
[src:biomass/arcology] Most proposals to build real arcologies have failed due to financial, structural or conceptual shortcomings.
[src:biomass/arcology] Arcologies are therefore found primarily in fictional works.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Like all animals, humans carry vast numbers (approximately 1013 to 1014) of bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Most are in the gut, though there are many on the skin.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Most of the bacteria in and on the body are harmless or rendered so by the protective effects of the immune system, and many are beneficial, particularly the ones in the gut.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] However, several species of bacteria are pathogenic and cause infectious diseases, including cholera, syphilis, anthrax, leprosy, tuberculosis, tetanus and bubonic plague.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The most common fatal bacterial diseases are respiratory infections.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Antibiotics are used to treat bacterial infections and are also used in farming, making antibiotic resistance a growing problem.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Once regarded as plants constituting the class *Schizomycetes* ("fission fungi"), bacteria are now classified as prokaryotes.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Unlike cells of animals and other eukaryotes, bacterial cells contain circular chromosomes, do not contain a nucleus and rarely harbour membrane-bound organelles.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Although the term *bacteria* traditionally included all prokaryotes, the scientific classification changed after the discovery in the 1990s that prokaryotes consist of two very different groups of organisms that evolved from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] These evolutionary domains are called Bacteria and Archaea.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Unlike Archaea, bacteria contain ester-linked lipids in the cell membrane, possess elongation factors that are resistant to ADP-ribosylation by diphtheria toxin, use formylmethionine in protein synthesis initiation, and have numerous genetic differences, including a different 16S rRNA.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The word was first used to refer to bacteria in 1828.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Although an estimated 43,000 species of bacteria have been named, most of them have never been studied.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] In fact, just 10 bacterial species account for half of all publications, whereas nearly 75% of all named bacteria have no academic research devoted to them.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The best-studied species, *Escherichia coli*, has more than 300,000 studies published on it, but many of these papers likely use it only as a cloning vehicle to study other species, without providing any insight into its own biology.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] 90% of scientific studies on bacteria focus on less than 1% of species, mostly pathogenic bacteria relevant to human health.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] While *E. coli* is probably the best-studied bacterium, a quarter of its 4000 genes are poorly studied or remain uncharacterized.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria with minimal genomes (< 600 genes, e.g.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] *Mycoplasma*) usually have a large fraction of their genes functionally characterized, given that most of them are essential and conserved in many other species.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The ancestors of bacteria were unicellular microorganisms that were the first forms of life to appear on Earth, about 4 billion years ago.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] For about 3 billion years, most organisms were microscopic, and bacteria and archaea were the dominant forms of life.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Although bacterial fossils exist, such as stromatolites, their lack of distinctive morphology prevents them from being used to examine the history of bacterial evolution, or to date the time of origin of a particular bacterial species.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] However, gene sequences can be used to reconstruct the bacterial phylogeny, and these studies indicate that bacteria diverged first from the archaeal/eukaryotic lineage.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The most recent common ancestor (MRCA) of bacteria and archaea was probably a hyperthermophile that lived about 2.5 billion–3.2 billion years ago.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The earliest life on land may have been bacteria some 3.22 billion years ago.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria were also involved in the second great evolutionary divergence, that of the archaea and eukaryotes.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Here, eukaryotes resulted from the entering of ancient bacteria into endosymbiotic associations with the ancestors of eukaryotic cells, which were themselves possibly related to the Archaea.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] This involved the engulfment by proto-eukaryotic cells of alphaproteobacterial symbionts to form either mitochondria or hydrogenosomes, which are still found in all known Eukarya (sometimes in highly reduced form, e.g. in species of amitochondrial protozoa).
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Later, some eukaryotes that already contained mitochondria also engulfed cyanobacteria-like organisms, leading to the formation of chloroplasts in algae and plants.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria are ubiquitous, living in every possible habitat on the planet including soil, underwater, deep in Earth's crust and even such extreme environments as acidic hot springs and radioactive waste.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] There are thought to be approximately 2×1030 bacteria on Earth, forming a biomass that is only exceeded by plants.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] They are abundant in lakes and oceans, in arctic ice, and geothermal springs where they provide the nutrients needed to sustain life by converting dissolved compounds, such as hydrogen sulphide and methane, to energy.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Most do not cause diseases, are beneficial to their environments, and are essential for life.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The soil is a rich source of bacteria and a few grams contain around a thousand million of them.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] They are all essential to soil ecology, breaking down toxic waste and recycling nutrients.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] They are even found in the atmosphere and one cubic metre of air holds around one hundred million bacterial cells.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The oceans and seas harbour around 3 × 1026 bacteria which provide up to 50% of the oxygen humans breathe.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Only around 2% of bacterial species have been fully studied.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria display a wide diversity of shapes and sizes.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cells are about one-tenth the size of eukaryotic cells and are typically 0.5–5.0 micrometres in length.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] However, a few species are visible to the unaided eye—for example, *Thiomargarita namibiensis* is up to half a millimetre long, *Epulopiscium fishelsoni* reaches 0.7 mm, and *Thiomargarita magnifica* can reach even 2 cm in length, which is 50 times larger than other known bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Among the smallest bacteria are members of the genus *Mycoplasma*, which measure only 0.3 micrometres, as small as the largest viruses.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria may be even smaller, but these ultramicrobacteria are not well-studied.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species are either spherical, called *cocci* (*singular coccus*, from Greek *kókkos*, grain, seed), or rod-shaped, called *bacilli* (*sing*. bacillus, from Latin *baculus*, stick).
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, called *vibrio*, are shaped like slightly curved rods or comma-shaped; others can be spiral-shaped, called *spirilla*, or tightly coiled, called *spirochaetes*.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] A small number of other unusual shapes have been described, such as star-shaped bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] This wide variety of shapes is determined by the bacterial cell wall and cytoskeleton and is important because it can influence the ability of bacteria to acquire nutrients, attach to surfaces, swim through liquids and escape predators.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species exist as single cells; others associate in characteristic patterns: *Neisseria* forms diploids (pairs), streptococci form chains, and staphylococci group together in "bunch of grapes" clusters.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can also group to form larger multicellular structures, such as the elongated filaments of *Actinomycetota* species, the aggregates of *Myxobacteria* species, and the complex hyphae of *Streptomyces* species.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] These multicellular structures are often only seen in certain conditions.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] For example, when starved of amino acids, myxobacteria detect surrounding cells in a process known as quorum sensing, migrate towards each other, and aggregate to form fruiting bodies up to 500 micrometres long and containing approximately 100,000 bacterial cells.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] In these fruiting bodies, the bacteria perform separate tasks; for example, about one in ten cells migrate to the top of a fruiting body and differentiate into a specialised dormant state called a myxospore, which is more resistant to drying and other adverse environmental conditions.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often attach to surfaces and form dense aggregations called biofilms and larger formations known as microbial mats.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] These biofilms and mats can range from a few micrometres in thickness to up to half a metre in depth, and may contain multiple species of bacteria, protists and archaea.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria living in biofilms display a complex arrangement of cells and extracellular components, forming secondary structures, such as microcolonies, through which there are networks of channels to enable better diffusion of nutrients.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] In natural environments, such as soil or the surfaces of plants, the majority of bacteria are bound to surfaces in biofilms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Biofilms are also important in medicine, as these structures are often present during chronic bacterial infections or in infections of implanted medical devices, and bacteria protected within biofilms are much harder to kill than individual isolated bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The bacterial cell is surrounded by a cell membrane, which is made primarily of phospholipids.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] This membrane encloses the contents of the cell and acts as a barrier to hold nutrients, proteins and other essential components within the cell.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Unlike eukaryotic cells, bacteria usually lack large membrane-bound structures in their cytoplasm such as a nucleus, mitochondria, chloroplasts and the other organelles present in eukaryotic cells.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] However, some bacteria have protein-bound organelles in the cytoplasm which compartmentalise aspects of bacterial metabolism, such as the carboxysome.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Additionally, bacteria have a multi-component cytoskeleton to control the localisation of proteins and nucleic acids within the cell, and to manage the process of cell division.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Many important biochemical reactions, such as energy generation, occur due to differences in concentration of molecules across membranes, creating a electrochemical potential analogous to a battery.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The general lack of internal membranes in bacteria means these reactions, such as electron transport, occur across the cell membrane between the cytoplasm and the outside of the cell or periplasm.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] However, in many photosynthetic bacteria, the plasma membrane is highly folded and fills most of the cell with layers of light-gathering membrane.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] These light-gathering complexes may even form lipid-enclosed structures called chlorosomes in green sulfur bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria do not have a membrane-bound nucleus, and their genetic material is typically a single circular bacterial chromosome of DNA located in the cytoplasm in an irregularly shaped body called the nucleoid.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The nucleoid contains the chromosome with its associated proteins and RNA.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Like all other organisms, bacteria contain ribosomes for the production of proteins, but the structure of the bacterial ribosome is different from that of eukaryotes and archaea.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Its translation process is also different.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria produce intracellular nutrient storage granules, such as glycogen, polyphosphate, sulfur or polyhydroxyalkanoates.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria such as the photosynthetic cyanobacteria, produce internal gas vacuoles, which they use to regulate their buoyancy, allowing them to move up or down into water layers with different light intensities and nutrient levels.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Around the outside of the cell membrane is the cell wall.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are made of peptidoglycan (also called murein), which is made from polysaccharide chains cross-linked by peptides containing D-amino acids.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are different from the cell walls of plants and fungi, which are made of cellulose and chitin, respectively.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The cell wall of bacteria is also distinct from that of archaea, which do not contain peptidoglycan.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The cell wall is essential to the survival of many bacteria, and the antibiotic penicillin (produced by a fungus called *Penicillium*) is able to kill bacteria by inhibiting a step in the synthesis of peptidoglycan.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] There are broadly speaking two different types of cell wall in bacteria, that classify bacteria into Gram-positive bacteria and Gram-negative bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The names originate from the reaction of cells to the Gram stain, a long-standing test for the classification of bacterial species.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Gram-positive bacteria possess a thick cell wall containing many layers of peptidoglycan and teichoic acids.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] In contrast, Gram-negative bacteria have a relatively thin cell wall consisting of a few layers of peptidoglycan surrounded by a second lipid membrane containing lipopolysaccharides and lipoproteins.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have the Gram-negative cell wall, and only members of the *Bacillota* group and actinomycetota (previously known as the low G+C and high G+C Gram-positive bacteria, respectively) have the alternative Gram-positive arrangement.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] These differences in structure can produce differences in antibiotic susceptibility; for instance, vancomycin can kill only Gram-positive bacteria and is ineffective against Gram-negative pathogens, such as *Haemophilus influenzae* or *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria have cell wall structures that are neither classically Gram-positive or Gram-negative.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] This includes clinically important bacteria such as mycobacteria which have a thick peptidoglycan cell wall like a Gram-positive bacterium, but also a second outer layer of lipids.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] In many bacteria, an S-layer of rigidly arrayed protein molecules covers the outside of the cell.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] This layer provides chemical and physical protection for the cell surface and can act as a macromolecular diffusion barrier.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] S-layers have diverse functions and are known to act as virulence factors in *Campylobacter* species and contain surface enzymes in *Bacillus stearothermophilus*.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Flagella are rigid protein structures, about 20 nanometres in diameter and up to 20 micrometres in length, that are used for motility.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Flagella are driven by the energy released by the transfer of ions down an electrochemical gradient across the cell membrane.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae (sometimes called "attachment pili") are fine filaments of protein, usually 2–10 nanometres in diameter and up to several micrometres in length.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] They are distributed over the surface of the cell, and resemble fine hairs when seen under the electron microscope.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae are believed to be involved in attachment to solid surfaces or to other cells, and are essential for the virulence of some bacterial pathogens.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Pili (*sing*. pilus) are cellular appendages, slightly larger than fimbriae, that can transfer genetic material between bacterial cells in a process called conjugation where they are called conjugation pili or sex pili (see bacterial genetics, below).
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] They can also generate movement where they are called type IV pili.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Glycocalyx is produced by many bacteria to surround their cells, and varies in structural complexity: ranging from a disorganised slime layer of extracellular polymeric substances to a highly structured capsule.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] These structures can protect cells from engulfment by eukaryotic cells such as macrophages (part of the human immune system).
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] They can also act as antigens and be involved in cell recognition, as well as aiding attachment to surfaces and the formation of biofilms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The assembly of these extracellular structures is dependent on bacterial secretion systems.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] These transfer proteins from the cytoplasm into the periplasm or into the environment around the cell.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Many types of secretion systems are known and these structures are often essential for the virulence of pathogens, so are intensively studied.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Some genera of Gram-positive bacteria, such as *Bacillus*, *Clostridium*, *Sporohalobacter*, *Anaerobacter*, and *Heliobacterium*, can form highly resistant, dormant structures called *endospores*.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Endospores develop within the cytoplasm of the cell; generally, a single endospore develops in each cell.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Each endospore contains a core of DNA and ribosomes surrounded by a cortex layer and protected by a multilayer rigid coat composed of peptidoglycan and a variety of proteins.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Endospores show no detectable metabolism and can survive extreme physical and chemical stresses, such as high levels of UV light, gamma radiation, detergents, disinfectants, heat, freezing, pressure, and desiccation.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] In this dormant state, these organisms may remain viable for millions of years.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Endospores even allow bacteria to survive exposure to the vacuum and radiation of outer space, leading to the possibility that bacteria could be distributed throughout the universe by space dust, meteoroids, asteroids, comets, planetoids, or directed panspermia.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] *Clostridioides difficile* infection, a common problem in healthcare settings, is caused by spore-forming bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria exhibit an extremely wide variety of metabolic types.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The distribution of metabolic traits within a group of bacteria has traditionally been used to define their taxonomy, but these traits often do not correspond with modern genetic classifications.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolism is classified into nutritional groups on the basis of three major criteria: the source of energy, the electron donors used, and the source of carbon used for growth.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Phototrophic bacteria derive energy from light using photosynthesis, while chemotrophic bacteria breaking down chemical compounds through oxidation, driving metabolism by transferring electrons from a given electron donor to a terminal electron acceptor in a redox reaction.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Chemotrophs are further divided by the types of compounds they use to transfer electrons.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria that derive electrons from inorganic compounds such as hydrogen, carbon monoxide, or ammonia are called lithotrophs, while those that use organic compounds are called organotrophs.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Still, more specifically, aerobic organisms use oxygen as the terminal electron acceptor, while anaerobic organisms use other compounds such as nitrate, sulfate, or carbon dioxide.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria, called heterotrophs, derive their carbon from other organic carbon.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Others, such as cyanobacteria and some purple bacteria, are autotrophic, meaning they obtain cellular carbon by fixing carbon dioxide.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] In unusual circumstances, the gas methane can be used by methanotrophic bacteria as both a source of electrons and a substrate for carbon anabolism.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] In many ways, bacterial metabolism provides traits that are useful for ecological stability and for human society.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] For example, diazotrophs have the ability to fix nitrogen gas using the enzyme nitrogenase.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] This trait, which can be found in bacteria of most metabolic types listed above, leads to the ecologically important processes of denitrification, sulfate reduction, and acetogenesis, respectively.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolic processes are important drivers in biological responses to pollution; for example, sulfate-reducing bacteria are largely responsible for the production of the highly toxic forms of mercury (methyl- and dimethylmercury) in the environment.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Nonrespiratory anaerobes use fermentation to generate energy and reducing power, secreting metabolic by-products (such as ethanol in brewing) as waste.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Facultative anaerobes can switch between fermentation and different terminal electron acceptors depending on the environmental conditions in which they find themselves.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Unlike in multicellular organisms, increases in cell size (cell growth) and reproduction by cell division are tightly linked in unicellular organisms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria grow to a fixed size and then reproduce through binary fission, a form of asexual reproduction.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Under optimal conditions, bacteria can grow and divide extremely rapidly, and some bacterial populations can double as quickly as every 17 minutes.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] In cell division, two identical clone daughter cells are produced.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, while still reproducing asexually, form more complex reproductive structures that help disperse the newly formed daughter cells.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Examples include fruiting body formation by myxobacteria and aerial hyphae formation by *Streptomyces* species, or budding.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Budding involves a cell forming a protrusion that breaks away and produces a daughter cell.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] In the laboratory, bacteria are usually grown using solid or liquid media.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Solid growth media, such as agar plates, are used to isolate pure cultures of a bacterial strain.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] However, liquid growth media are used when the measurement of growth or large volumes of cells are required.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Growth in stirred liquid media occurs as an even cell suspension, making the cultures easy to divide and transfer, although isolating single bacteria from liquid media is difficult.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The use of selective media (media with specific nutrients added or deficient, or with antibiotics added) can help identify specific organisms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Most laboratory techniques for growing bacteria use high levels of nutrients to produce large amounts of cells cheaply and quickly.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] However, in natural environments, nutrients are limited, meaning that bacteria cannot continue to reproduce indefinitely.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] This nutrient limitation has led the evolution of different growth strategies (see r/K selection theory).
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Some organisms can grow extremely rapidly when nutrients become available, such as the formation of algal and cyanobacterial blooms that often occur in lakes during the summer.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Other organisms have adaptations to harsh environments, such as the production of multiple antibiotics by *Streptomyces* that inhibit the growth of competing microorganisms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] In nature, many organisms live in communities (e.g., biofilms) that may allow for increased supply of nutrients and protection from environmental stresses.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] These relationships can be essential for growth of a particular organism or group of organisms (syntrophy).
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] When a population of bacteria first enter a high-nutrient environment that allows growth, the cells need to adapt to their new environment.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The first phase of growth is the lag phase, a period of slow growth when the cells are adapting to the high-nutrient environment and preparing for fast growth.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The lag phase has high biosynthesis rates, as proteins necessary for rapid growth are produced.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The second phase of growth is the logarithmic phase, also known as the exponential phase.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The log phase is marked by rapid exponential growth.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The rate at which cells grow during this phase is known as the *growth rate* (*k*), and the time it takes the cells to double is known as the *generation time* (*g*).
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] During log phase, nutrients are metabolised at maximum speed until one of the nutrients is depleted and starts limiting growth.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The third phase of growth is the *stationary phase* and is caused by depleted nutrients.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The cells reduce their metabolic activity and consume non-essential cellular proteins.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The stationary phase is a transition from rapid growth to a stress response state and there is increased expression of genes involved in DNA repair, antioxidant metabolism and nutrient transport.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The final phase is the death phase where the bacteria run out of nutrients and die.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] There are many exceptions to this; for example, some *Streptomyces* and *Borrelia* species contain a single linear chromosome, while some bacteria including species of *Vibrio* contain more than one chromosome.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria contain plasmids, small extra-chromosomal molecules of DNA that may contain genes for various useful functions such as antibiotic resistance, metabolic capabilities, or various virulence factors.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Whether they have a single chromosome or more than one, almost all bacteria have a haploid genome.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] This means that they have only one copy of each gene encoding proteins.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] This is in contrast to eukaryotes, which are diploid or polyploid, meaning they have two or more copies of each gene.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] This means that unlike humans, who may still be able to create a protein if the gene becomes mutated (since the human genome has an extra copy in each cell), a bacterium will be completely unable to create the protein if its gene incurs an inactivating mutation.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacterial genomes usually encode a few hundred to a few thousand genes.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The genes in bacterial genomes are usually a single continuous stretch of DNA.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Although several different types of introns do exist in bacteria, these are much rarer than in eukaryotes.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria, as asexual organisms, inherit an identical copy of the parent's genome and are clonal.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] However, all bacteria can evolve by selection on changes to their genetic material DNA caused by genetic recombination or mutations.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Mutations arise from errors made during the replication of DNA or from exposure to mutagens.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Mutation rates vary widely among different species of bacteria and even among different clones of a single species of bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Genetic changes in bacterial genomes emerge from either random mutation during replication or "stress-directed mutation", where genes involved in a particular growth-limiting process have an increased mutation rate.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria transfer genetic material between cells.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] First, bacteria can take up exogenous DNA from their environment in a process called transformation.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria can naturally take up DNA from the environment, while others must be chemically altered in order to induce them to take up DNA.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The development of competence in nature is usually associated with stressful environmental conditions and seems to be an adaptation for facilitating repair of DNA damage in recipient cells.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Second, bacteriophages can integrate into the bacterial chromosome, introducing foreign DNA in a process known as transduction.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Many types of bacteriophage exist; some infect and lyse their host bacteria, while others insert into the bacterial chromosome.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Third, bacteria can transfer genetic material through direct cell contact via conjugation.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] In such cases, gene acquisition from other bacteria or the environment is called horizontal gene transfer and may be common under natural conditions.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria are motile (able to move themselves) and do so using a variety of mechanisms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The best studied of these are flagella, long filaments that are turned by a motor at the base to generate propeller-like movement.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The bacterial flagellum is made of about 20 proteins, with approximately another 30 proteins required for its regulation and assembly.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The flagellum is a rotating structure driven by a reversible motor at the base that uses the electrochemical gradient across the membrane for power.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can use flagella in different ways to generate different kinds of movement.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria (such as *E. coli*) have two distinct modes of movement: forward movement (swimming) and tumbling.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The tumbling allows them to reorient and makes their movement a three-dimensional random walk.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The flagella of a group of bacteria, the spirochaetes, are found between two membranes in the periplasmic space.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] They have a distinctive helical body that twists about as it moves.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Two other types of bacterial motion are called twitching motility that relies on a structure called the type IV pilus, and gliding motility, that uses other mechanisms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] In twitching motility, the rod-like pilus extends out from the cell, binds some substrate, and then retracts, pulling the cell forward.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Motile bacteria are attracted or repelled by certain stimuli in behaviours called *taxes*: these include chemotaxis, phototaxis, energy taxis, and magnetotaxis.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] In one peculiar group, the myxobacteria, individual bacteria move together to form waves of cells that then differentiate to form fruiting bodies containing spores.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The myxobacteria move only when on solid surfaces, unlike *E. coli*, which is motile in liquid or solid media.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Several *Listeria* and *Shigella* species move inside host cells by usurping the cytoskeleton, which is normally used to move organelles inside the cell.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] By promoting actin polymerisation at one pole of their cells, they can form a kind of tail that pushes them through the host cell's cytoplasm.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] A few bacteria have chemical systems that generate light.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] This bioluminescence often occurs in bacteria that live in association with fish, and the light probably serves to attract fish or other large animals.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often function as multicellular aggregates known as biofilms, exchanging a variety of molecular signals for intercell communication and engaging in coordinated multicellular behaviour.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The communal benefits of multicellular cooperation include a cellular division of labour, accessing resources that cannot effectively be used by single cells, collectively defending against antagonists, and optimising population survival by differentiating into distinct cell types.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] For example, bacteria in biofilms can have more than five hundred times the increased resistance to antibacterial agents than individual "planktonic" bacteria of the same species.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] One type of intercellular communication by a molecular signal is called quorum sensing.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing determines whether the local population is dense enough to support investment in processes that are only successful if large numbers of similar organisms behave similarly, such as excreting digestive enzymes or emitting light.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing enables bacteria to coordinate gene expression and to produce, release, and detect autoinducers or pheromones that accumulate with the growth in cell population.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Classification seeks to describe the diversity of bacterial species by naming and grouping organisms based on similarities.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can be classified on the basis of cell structure, cellular metabolism or on differences in cell components, such as DNA, fatty acids, pigments, antigens and quinones.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] While these schemes allowed the identification and classification of **bacterial strains**, it was unclear whether these differences represented variation between distinct species or between strains of the same species.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] This uncertainty was due to the lack of distinctive structures in most bacteria, as well as lateral gene transfer between unrelated species.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Due to lateral gene transfer, some closely related bacteria can have very different morphologies and metabolisms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Classification of bacteria is determined by publication in the International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology, and Bergey's Manual of Systematic Bacteriology.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The International Committee on Systematic Bacteriology (ICSB) maintains international rules for the naming of bacteria and taxonomic categories and for the ranking of them in the International Code of Nomenclature of Bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Historically, bacteria were considered a part of the Plantae, the plant kingdom, and were called "Schizomycetes" (fission-fungi).
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] For this reason, collective bacteria and other microorganisms in a host are often called "flora".
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The term "bacteria" was traditionally applied to all microscopic, single-cell prokaryotes.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] However, molecular systematics showed prokaryotic life to consist of two separate domains, originally called Eubacteria and Archaebacteria, but now called Bacteria and Archaea that evolved independently from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The archaea and eukaryotes are more closely related to each other than either is to the bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] These two domains, along with Eukarya, are the basis of the three-domain system, which is currently the most widely used classification system in microbiology.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] However, due to the relatively recent introduction of molecular systematics and a rapid increase in the number of genome sequences that are available, bacterial classification remains a changing and expanding field.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] For example, Cavalier-Smith argued that the Archaea and Eukaryotes evolved from Gram-positive bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The identification of bacteria in the laboratory is particularly relevant in medicine, where the correct treatment is determined by the bacterial species causing an infection.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Consequently, the need to identify human pathogens was a major impetus for the development of techniques to identify bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Once a pathogenic organism has been isolated, it can be further characterised by its morphology, growth patterns (such as aerobic or anaerobic growth), patterns of hemolysis, and staining.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The *Gram stain*, developed in 1884 by Hans Christian Gram, characterises bacteria based on the structural characteristics of their cell walls.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The thick layers of peptidoglycan in the "Gram-positive" cell wall stain purple, while the thin "Gram-negative" cell wall appears pink.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] By combining morphology and Gram-staining, most bacteria can be classified as belonging to one of four groups (Gram-positive cocci, Gram-positive bacilli, Gram-negative cocci and Gram-negative bacilli).
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Some organisms are best identified by stains other than the Gram stain, particularly mycobacteria or *Nocardia*, which show acid fastness on Ziehl–Neelsen or similar stains.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Culture techniques are designed to promote the growth and identify particular bacteria while restricting the growth of the other bacteria in the sample.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Often these techniques are designed for specific specimens; for example, a sputum sample will be treated to identify organisms that cause pneumonia, while stool specimens are cultured on selective media to identify organisms that cause diarrhea while preventing growth of non-pathogenic bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Specimens that are normally sterile, such as blood, urine or spinal fluid, are cultured under conditions designed to grow all possible organisms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Other organisms may need to be identified by their growth in special media, or by other techniques, such as serology.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] As with bacterial classification, identification of bacteria is increasingly using molecular methods, and mass spectroscopy.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have not been characterised and there are many species that cannot be grown in the laboratory.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Diagnostics using DNA-based tools, such as polymerase chain reaction, are increasingly popular due to their specificity and speed, compared to culture-based methods.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] These methods also allow the detection and identification of "viable but nonculturable" cells that are metabolically active but non-dividing.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] The main way to characterize and classify these bacteria is to isolate their DNA from environmental samples and mass-sequence them.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] This approach has identified thousands, if not millions of candidate species.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p01] Based on some estimates, more than 43,000 species of bacteria have been described, but attempts to estimate the true number of bacterial diversity have ranged from 107 to 109 total species—and even these diverse estimates may be off by many orders of magnitude.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Despite their apparent simplicity, bacteria can form complex associations with other organisms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] These symbiotic associations can be divided into parasitism, mutualism and commensalism.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] The word "commensalism" is derived from the word "commensal", meaning "eating at the same table" and all plants and animals are colonised by commensal bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] In humans and other animals, trillions of them live on the skin, the airways, the gut and other orifices.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Referred to as "normal flora", or "commensals", these bacteria usually cause no harm but may occasionally invade other sites of the body and cause infection.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] *Escherichia coli* is a commensal in the human gut but can cause urinary tract infections.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Similarly, streptococci, which are part of the normal flora of the human mouth, can cause heart disease.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Some species of bacteria kill and then consume other microorganisms; these species are called *predatory bacteria*.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] These include organisms such as *Myxococcus xanthus*, which forms swarms of cells that kill and digest any bacteria they encounter.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Other bacterial predators either attach to their prey in order to digest them and absorb nutrients or invade another cell and multiply inside the cytosol.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] These predatory bacteria are thought to have evolved from saprophages that consumed dead microorganisms, through adaptations that allowed them to entrap and kill other organisms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Certain bacteria form close spatial associations that are essential for their survival.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] One such mutualistic association, called interspecies hydrogen transfer, occurs between clusters of anaerobic bacteria that consume organic acids, such as butyric acid or propionic acid, and produce hydrogen, and methanogenic archaea that consume hydrogen.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] The bacteria in this association are unable to consume the organic acids as this reaction produces hydrogen that accumulates in their surroundings.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Only the intimate association with the hydrogen-consuming archaea keeps the hydrogen concentration low enough to allow the bacteria to grow.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] In soil, microorganisms that reside in the rhizosphere (a zone that includes the root surface and the soil that adheres to the root after gentle shaking) carry out nitrogen fixation, converting nitrogen gas to nitrogenous compounds.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] This serves to provide an easily absorbable form of nitrogen for many plants, which cannot fix nitrogen themselves.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Many other bacteria are found as symbionts in humans and other organisms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] The presence of this gut flora also inhibits the growth of potentially pathogenic bacteria (usually through competitive exclusion) and these beneficial bacteria are consequently sold as probiotic dietary supplements.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Nearly all animal life is dependent on bacteria for survival as only bacteria and some archaea possess the genes and enzymes necessary to synthesise vitamin B12, also known as cobalamin, and provide it through the food chain.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Vitamin B12 is a water-soluble vitamin that is involved in the metabolism of every cell of the human body.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] It is a cofactor in DNA synthesis and in both fatty acid and amino acid metabolism.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] It is particularly important in the normal functioning of the nervous system via its role in the synthesis of myelin.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] The body is continually exposed to many species of bacteria, including beneficial commensals, which grow on the skin and mucous membranes, and saprophytes, which grow mainly in the soil and in decaying matter.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] The blood and tissue fluids contain nutrients sufficient to sustain the growth of many bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] The body has defence mechanisms that enable it to resist microbial invasion of its tissues and give it a natural immunity or innate resistance against many microorganisms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Unlike some viruses, bacteria evolve relatively slowly so many bacterial diseases also occur in other animals.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] If bacteria form a parasitic association with other organisms, they are classed as pathogens.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] A pathogenic cause for a known medical disease may only be discovered many years later, as was the case with *Helicobacter pylori* and peptic ulcer disease.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Bacterial diseases are also important in agriculture, and bacteria cause leaf spot, fire blight and wilts in plants, as well as Johne's disease, mastitis, salmonella and anthrax in farm animals.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Each species of pathogen has a characteristic spectrum of interactions with its human hosts.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Some organisms, such as *Staphylococcus* or *Streptococcus*, can cause skin infections, pneumonia, meningitis and sepsis, a systemic inflammatory response producing shock, massive vasodilation and death.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Yet these organisms are also part of the normal human flora and usually exist on the skin or in the nose without causing any disease at all.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Other organisms invariably cause disease in humans, such as *Rickettsia*, which are obligate intracellular parasites able to grow and reproduce only within the cells of other organisms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] One species of *Rickettsia* causes typhus, while another causes Rocky Mountain spotted fever.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] *Chlamydia*, another phylum of obligate intracellular parasites, contains species that can cause pneumonia or urinary tract infection and may be involved in coronary heart disease.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Some species, such as *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, *Burkholderia cenocepacia*, and *Mycobacterium avium*, are opportunistic pathogens and cause disease mainly in people who are immunosuppressed or have cystic fibrosis.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Some bacteria produce toxins, which cause diseases.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] These are endotoxins, which come from broken bacterial cells, and exotoxins, which are produced by bacteria and released into the environment.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] The bacterium *Clostridium botulinum* for example, produces a powerful exotoxin that cause respiratory paralysis, and *Salmonellae* produce an endotoxin that causes gastroenteritis.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Some exotoxins can be converted to toxoids, which are used as vaccines to prevent the disease.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Bacterial infections may be treated with antibiotics, which are classified as bacteriocidal if they kill bacteria or bacteriostatic if they just prevent bacterial growth.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] There are many types of antibiotics, and each class inhibits a process that is different in the pathogen from that found in the host.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] An example of how antibiotics produce selective toxicity are chloramphenicol and puromycin, which inhibit the bacterial ribosome, but not the structurally different eukaryotic ribosome.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Antibiotics are used both in treating human disease and in intensive farming to promote animal growth, where they may be contributing to the rapid development of antibiotic resistance in bacterial populations.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Infections can be prevented by antiseptic measures such as sterilising the skin prior to piercing it with the needle of a syringe, and by proper care of indwelling catheters.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Surgical and dental instruments are also sterilised to prevent contamination by bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Disinfectants such as bleach are used to kill bacteria or other pathogens on surfaces to prevent contamination and further reduce the risk of infection.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Bacteria, often lactic acid bacteria, such as *Lactobacillus* species and *Lactococcus* species, in combination with yeasts and moulds, have been used for thousands of years in the preparation of fermented foods, such as cheese, pickles, soy sauce, sauerkraut, vinegar, wine, and yogurt.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] The ability of bacteria to degrade a variety of organic compounds is remarkable and has been used in waste processing and bioremediation.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Bacteria capable of digesting the hydrocarbons in petroleum are often used to clean up oil spills.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Fertiliser was added to some of the beaches in Prince William Sound in an attempt to promote the growth of these naturally occurring bacteria after the 1989 *Exxon Valdez* oil spill.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] These efforts were effective on beaches that were not too thickly covered in oil.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Bacteria are also used for the bioremediation of industrial toxic wastes.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] In the chemical industry, bacteria are most important in the production of enantiomerically pure chemicals for use as pharmaceuticals or agrichemicals.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Bacteria can also be used in place of pesticides in biological pest control.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] This commonly involves *Bacillus thuringiensis* (also called BT), a Gram-positive, soil-dwelling bacterium.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Subspecies of this bacteria are used as Lepidopteran-specific insecticides under trade names such as Dipel and Thuricide.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Because of their specificity, these pesticides are regarded as environmentally friendly, with little or no effect on humans, wildlife, pollinators, and most other beneficial insects.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Because of their ability to quickly grow and the relative ease with which they can be manipulated, bacteria are the workhorses for the fields of molecular biology, genetics, and biochemistry.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] By making mutations in bacterial DNA and examining the resulting phenotypes, scientists can determine the function of genes, enzymes, and metabolic pathways in bacteria, then apply this knowledge to more complex organisms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] This aim of understanding the biochemistry of a cell reaches its most complex expression in the synthesis of huge amounts of enzyme kinetic and gene expression data into mathematical models of entire organisms.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] This is achievable in some well-studied bacteria, with models of *Escherichia coli* metabolism now being produced and tested.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] This understanding of bacterial metabolism and genetics allows the use of biotechnology to bioengineer bacteria for the production of therapeutic proteins, such as insulin, growth factors, or antibodies.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Because of their importance for research in general, samples of bacterial strains are isolated and preserved in Biological Resource Centres.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] This ensures the availability of the strain to scientists worldwide.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were first observed by the Dutch microscopist Antonie van Leeuwenhoek in 1676, using a single-lens microscope of his own design.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Leeuwenhoek did not recognize bacteria as a distinct category of microorganisms, referring to all microorganisms that he observed, including bacteria, protists, and microscopic animals, as animalcules.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] He published his observations in a series of letters to the Royal Society of London.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were Leeuwenhoek's most remarkable microscopic discovery.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Their size was just at the limit of what his simple lenses could resolve, and, in one of the most striking hiatuses in the history of science, no one else would see them again for over a century.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] His observations also included protozoans, and his findings were looked at again in the light of the more recent findings of cell theory.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Christian Gottfried Ehrenberg introduced the word "bacterium" in 1828.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] In fact, his *Bacterium* was a genus that contained non-spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria, as opposed to *Bacillus*, a genus of spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria defined by Ehrenberg in 1835.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Louis Pasteur demonstrated in 1859 that the growth of microorganisms causes the fermentation process and that this growth is not due to spontaneous generation (yeasts and molds, commonly associated with fermentation, are not bacteria, but rather fungi).
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Along with his contemporary Robert Koch, Pasteur was an early advocate of the germ theory of disease.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Before them, Ignaz Semmelweis and Joseph Lister had realised the importance of sanitised hands in medical work.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Semmelweis, who in the 1840s formulated his rules for handwashing in the hospital, prior to the advent of germ theory, attributed disease to "decomposing animal organic matter".
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] His ideas were rejected and his book on the topic condemned by the medical community.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] After Lister, however, doctors started sanitising their hands in the 1870s.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Robert Koch, a pioneer in medical microbiology, worked on cholera, anthrax and tuberculosis.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] In his research into tuberculosis, Koch finally proved the germ theory, for which he received a Nobel Prize in 1905.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] In Koch's postulates, he set out criteria to test if an organism is the cause of a disease, and these postulates are still used today.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Ferdinand Cohn is said to be a founder of bacteriology, studying bacteria from 1870.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Cohn was the first to classify bacteria based on their morphology.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Though it was known in the nineteenth century that bacteria are the cause of many diseases, no effective antibacterial treatments were available.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] In 1910, Paul Ehrlich developed the first antibiotic, by changing dyes that selectively stained *Treponema pallidum*—the spirochaete that causes syphilis—into compounds that selectively killed the pathogen.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] Ehrlich, who had been awarded a 1908 Nobel Prize for his work on immunology, pioneered the use of stains to detect and identify bacteria, with his work being the basis of the Gram stain and the Ziehl–Neelsen stain.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] A major step forward in the study of bacteria came in 1977 when Carl Woese recognised that archaea have a separate line of evolutionary descent from bacteria.
[src:biomass/bacteria-p02] This new phylogenetic taxonomy depended on the sequencing of 16S ribosomal RNA and divided prokaryotes into two evolutionary domains, as part of the three-domain system.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A **bicycle**, also called a **pedal cycle**, **bike**, **push-bike** or **cycle**, is a human-powered or motor-assisted, pedal-driven, single-track vehicle, with two wheels attached to a frame, one behind the other.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A bicycle rider is called a cyclist, or bicyclist.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The bicycle was invented in Europe in the 19th century.
[src:biomass/bicycle] By the early 21st century, there were more than 1 billion bicycles.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycles are the principal means of transport in many regions.
[src:biomass/bicycle] They are also popular for recreation, and have been adapted for use as children's toys.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycles are used for commuting, shopping, fitness, military and police applications, courier services, bicycle racing, and artistic cycling.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The basic shape and configuration of a typical upright or "safety" bicycle, has changed little since the first chain-driven model was developed around 1885.
[src:biomass/bicycle] However, many details have been improved, especially since the advent of modern materials and computer-aided design.
[src:biomass/bicycle] These have allowed for a proliferation of specialized designs for many types of cycling.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In the 21st century, electric bicycles have become popular.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The bicycle's invention has had an enormous effect on society, both in terms of culture and of advancing modern industrial methods.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Several components that played a key role in the development of the car were initially invented for use in the bicycle, including ball bearings, pneumatic tires, chain-driven sprockets, and tension-spoked wheels.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The first known appearance in English print of the word *bicycle* was in *The Daily News* in 1868, to describe "Bysicles and trysicles" on the "Champs Elysées and Bois de Boulogne".
[src:biomass/bicycle] The word was first used in 1828 in French to describe a two-wheeled chaise, a horse-drawn carriage.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The design of the bicycle was an advance on the velocipede, although the words were used with some degree of overlap for a time.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Other words for bicycle include "bike", "pushbike", "pedal cycle", or "cycle".
[src:biomass/bicycle] In Unicode, the code point for "bicycle" is U+1F6B2.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The entity `&#x1F6B2;` in HTML produces 🚲.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The "dandy horse", also called *Draisienne* or *Laufmaschine* ("running machine"), was the first human means of transport to use only two wheels in tandem and was invented by the German Baron Karl von Drais.
[src:biomass/bicycle] It is regarded as the first bicycle and von Drais is seen as the "father of the bicycle", but it did not have pedals.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Von Drais introduced it to the public in Mannheim in 1817 and in Paris in 1818.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The rider sat astride a wooden frame supported by two in-line wheels and pushed the vehicle along with their feet while steering the front wheel.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The first mechanically propelled, two-wheeled vehicle may have been built by Kirkpatrick MacMillan, a Scottish blacksmith, in 1839, although this claim is often disputed.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In the early 1860s, the Frenchmen Pierre Michaux and Pierre Lallement took bicycle design in a new direction by adding a mechanical crank drive with pedals on an enlarged front wheel (the velocipede).
[src:biomass/bicycle] Another French inventor named Douglas Grasso had a failed prototype of Pierre Lallement's bicycle several years earlier.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Several inventions followed using rear-wheel drive, the best known being the rod-driven velocipede by Scotsman Thomas McCall in 1869.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In the same year, bicycle wheels with wire spokes were patented by Eugène Meyer of Paris.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The French *vélocipède*, made of iron and wood, developed into the "penny-farthing" (historically known as an "ordinary bicycle", a retronym, since there was then no other kind).
[src:biomass/bicycle] It featured a tubular steel frame on which were mounted wire-spoked wheels with solid rubber tires.
[src:biomass/bicycle] These bicycles were difficult to mount, dismount and brake due to their high seat over the large front wheel.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In 1868, Rowley Turner, a sales agent of the Coventry Sewing Machine Company (which soon became the Coventry Machinists Company), brought a Michaux cycle to Coventry, England.
[src:biomass/bicycle] His uncle, Josiah Turner, and business partner James Starley, used this as a basis for the 'Coventry Model' in what became Britain's first cycle factory.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The *dwarf ordinary* addressed some of these faults by reducing the front wheel diameter and setting the seat further back.
[src:biomass/bicycle] This, in turn, required gearing—effected in a variety of ways—to efficiently use pedal power.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Having to both pedal and steer via the front wheel remained a problem.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Lawson, and Shergold solved this problem by introducing the chain drive (originated by the unsuccessful "bicyclette" of Englishman Henry Lawson), connecting the frame-mounted cranks to the rear wheel.
[src:biomass/bicycle] These models were known as safety bicycles, dwarf safeties, or upright bicycles for their lower seat height.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Although, without pneumatic tires, the ride of the smaller-wheeled bicycle would be much rougher than that of the larger-wheeled variety.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Starley's 1885 Rover, manufactured in Coventry is usually described as the first recognizably modern bicycle.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Soon, the *seat tube* was added, which created the modern bike's double-triangle *diamond frame*.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Further innovations increased comfort and ushered in a second bicycle craze, the 1890s *Golden Age of Bicycles*.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In 1888, Scotsman John Boyd Dunlop introduced the first practical pneumatic tire, which soon became universal.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Willie Hume demonstrated the supremacy of Dunlop's tyres in 1889, winning the tyre's first-ever races in Ireland and then England.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Soon after, the rear freewheel was developed, enabling the rider to coast.
[src:biomass/bicycle] This refinement led to the 1890s invention of coaster brakes.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Derailleur gears and hand-operated Bowden cable-pull brakes were also developed during these years, but were only slowly adopted by casual riders.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The Svea Velocipede with vertical pedal arrangement and locking hubs was introduced in 1892 by the Swedish engineers Fredrik Ljungström and Birger Ljungström.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In the 1870s, many cycling clubs flourished.
[src:biomass/bicycle] They were popular in a time when there were no cars on the market and the principal mode of transportation was horse-drawn vehicles.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Among the earliest clubs was The Bicycle Touring Club, which has operated since 1878.
[src:biomass/bicycle] By the turn of the century, cycling clubs flourished on both sides of the Atlantic, and touring and racing became widely popular.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The Raleigh Bicycle Company was founded in Nottingham, England in 1888.
[src:biomass/bicycle] It became the biggest bicycle manufacturer in the world, making over two million bikes per year.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycles and horse buggies were the two mainstays of private transportation just prior to the automobile, and the grading of smooth roads in the late 19th century was stimulated by the widespread advertising, production, and use of these devices.
[src:biomass/bicycle] More than 1 billion bicycles had been manufactured worldwide by the early 21st century.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycles are the most common vehicle of any kind in the world, and the most numerous model of any kind of vehicle, whether human-powered or motor vehicle, is the Chinese Flying Pigeon, with numbers exceeding 500 million.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycles are used for transportation, bicycle commuting, and utility cycling.
[src:biomass/bicycle] They are also used professionally by mail carriers, paramedics, police, messengers, and for deliveries.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Military uses of bicycles included communications, reconnaissance, troop movement, supply of provisions, and patrol, such as in bicycle infantries.
[src:biomass/bicycle] They are also used for fun, including bicycle touring, mountain biking, physical fitness, and play.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycle sports include racing, BMX racing, track racing, criterium, roller racing, sportives and time trials.
[src:biomass/bicycle] They are also used for entertainment and pleasure in other ways, such as in organised mass rides, artistic cycling and freestyle BMX.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The bicycle has been continually adapted and improved.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Modern materials and computer-aided design have made bicycles safer and more comfortable, and helped to create many more types of bicycle.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycles can be categorized in many different ways: by function, by number of riders, by general construction, by gearing or by means of propulsion.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The more common types include utility bicycles, mountain bicycles, racing bicycles, touring bicycles, hybrid bicycles, cruiser bicycles, BMX bikes and electric bicycles.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Less common are tandems, low riders, tall bikes, fixed gear, folding models, amphibious bicycles, cargo bikes and recumbents .
[src:biomass/bicycle] Unicycles, tricycles and quadracycles are not strictly bicycles, as they have respectively one, three and four wheels, but they are *cycles* and the qualifier "bi" is not used in some other languages, such as "velo" or "fiets".
[src:biomass/bicycle] A bicycle stays upright while moving forward by being steered so as to keep its center of mass over the wheels, that is in line with the resultant force of gravity and centrifugal force.
[src:biomass/bicycle] This steering is usually provided by the rider, but under certain conditions, may be provided by the bicycle itself.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The combined center of mass of a bicycle and its rider must lean into a turn.
[src:biomass/bicycle] This lean is induced by a method known as countersteering, which can be performed by the rider turning the handlebars directly with the hands or indirectly by leaning the bicycle.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Short-wheelbase or tall bicycles, when braking, can generate enough stopping force at the front wheel to flip longitudinally.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The act of purposefully using this force to lift the rear wheel and balance on the front without tipping over is a trick known as a stoppie, endo, or front wheelie.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The bicycle is extraordinarily efficient in both biological and mechanical terms.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The bicycle is the most efficient human-powered means of transportation in terms of energy a person must expend to travel a given distance, when travelling slowly or equipped with an aerodynamic fairing.
[src:biomass/bicycle] From a mechanical viewpoint, up to 99% of the energy delivered by the rider into the pedals is transmitted to the wheels, although the use of gearing mechanisms may reduce this by 10–15% and there is also a small amount of tire slip.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A human traveling on a bicycle at low to medium speeds of about 16–24 km/h (10–15 mph) uses only the power required to walk.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Air drag, which is proportional to the square of speed, requires dramatically higher power outputs as speeds increase.
[src:biomass/bicycle] If the rider is sitting upright, the rider's body creates about 75% of the total drag of the bicycle/rider combination.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Drag can be reduced by seating the rider in a more aerodynamically streamlined position.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Drag can also be reduced by covering the bicycle with an aerodynamic fairing.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The fastest recorded unpaced speed on a flat surface with a standing start was the hour record in 2016: over 92 km/h (57 mph) with a highly streamlined bicycle.
[src:biomass/bicycle] One bicycle may have up to a thousand parts.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Most modern bicycles have a frame with upright seating that looks much like the first chain-driven bike.
[src:biomass/bicycle] These upright bicycles frequently have a *diamond frame*, a truss consisting of two triangles: the front triangle and the rear triangle.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The front triangle consists of the top tube and down tube (connected by the head tube), and seat tube.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The head tube contains the headset, the set of bearings that allows the fork to turn smoothly for steering and balance.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The rear triangle consists of the seat tube, with the bottom bracket at the bottom, and paired *chain stays* and *seat stays*, connecting at the rear dropouts, where the axle for the rear wheel is held.
[src:biomass/bicycle] This design, referred to as a *step-through frame* or as an *open frame*, allows the rider to mount and dismount in a dignified way while wearing a skirt or dress.
[src:biomass/bicycle] While some women's bicycles continue to use this frame style, there is also a variation, the *mixte*, which splits the top tube laterally into two thinner top tubes that bypass the seat tube on each side and connect to the rear fork ends.
[src:biomass/bicycle] These are inherently more aerodynamic than upright versions, as the rider may lean back onto a support and operate pedals that are on about the same level as the seat.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The world's fastest bicycle is a recumbent bicycle but this type was banned from competition in 1934 by the Union Cycliste Internationale.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Historically, materials used in bicycles have followed a similar pattern as in aircraft, the goal being high strength and low weight.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Since the late 1930s, alloy steels have been used for frame and fork tubes in higher quality machines.
[src:biomass/bicycle] By the 1980s, aluminum welding techniques had improved to the point that aluminum tube could safely be used instead of steel.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Since then aluminum alloy frames and other components have become popular due to their light weight, and most mid-range bikes are now aluminum alloy.
[src:biomass/bicycle] More expensive bikes sometimes use titanium or more often carbon fibre laid-up in resin due to its significantly lighter weight and profiling ability, allowing designers to make a bike both stiff and compliant by arranging the angles of the laid-up fibres optimally.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Virtually all professional racing bicycles now use carbon fibre frames, as they have the best strength to weight ratio.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A typical modern carbon fiber frame can weigh less than 2 pounds (1 kg).
[src:biomass/bicycle] Wood since the beginning and Bamboo, a natural composite material with high strength-to-weight ratio and stiffness, have been used for bicycles since 1894.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Modern versions use bamboo for the primary frame with glued metal connections and parts.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The *drivetrain* begins with pedals which rotate the cranks, which are held in axis by the bottom bracket.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Most bicycles use a chain to transmit power to the rear wheel.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A very small number of bicycles use a shaft drive to transmit power.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Hydraulic bicycle transmissions have been built, but they can be inefficient and complex.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Since cyclists' legs are most efficient over a narrow range of pedaling speeds, or cadence, a variable gear ratio helps a cyclist to maintain an optimum pedalling speed while covering varied terrain.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Some, mainly utility, bicycles use hub gears with between 3 and 14 ratios, but most use the generally more efficient derailleur system, by which the chain is moved between different cogs called chainrings and sprockets to select a ratio.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A derailleur system normally has two derailleurs, or mechs, one at the front to select the chainring and another at the back to select the sprocket.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Most bikes have two or three chainrings, and from 5 to 12 sprockets on the back, with the number of theoretical gears calculated by multiplying front by back.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In reality, many gears overlap or require the chain to run diagonally, so the number of usable gears is fewer.
[src:biomass/bicycle] An alternative to chain drive is to use a toothed belt.
[src:biomass/bicycle] These work much the same as a chain, they are popular with commuters as they require little maintenance.
[src:biomass/bicycle] They are slightly less efficient than chains and cannot be shifted across a cassette of sprockets, and are used either as single speed or with a hub gear.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Different gears and ranges of gears are appropriate for different people and styles of cycling.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Multi-speed bicycles allow gear selection to suit the circumstances: a cyclist could use a high gear when cycling downhill, a medium gear when cycling on a flat road, and a low gear when cycling uphill.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In a lower gear, every turn of the pedals leads to fewer rotations of the rear wheel.
[src:biomass/bicycle] This allows the energy required to move the same distance to be distributed over more pedal turns, reducing fatigue when riding uphill, with a heavy load, or against strong winds.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A higher gear allows a cyclist to make fewer pedal turns to maintain a given speed, but with more effort per turn of the pedals.
[src:biomass/bicycle] With a *chain drive* transmission, a *chainring* attached to a crank drives the chain, which in turn rotates the rear wheel via the rear sprocket(s) (cassette or freewheel).
[src:biomass/bicycle] There are four gearing options: two-speed hub gear integrated with chain ring, up to 3 chain rings, up to 12 sprockets and hub gear built into rear wheel (3-speed to 14-speed).
[src:biomass/bicycle] The most common options are either a rear hub or multiple chain rings combined with multiple sprockets (other combinations of options are possible but less common).
[src:biomass/bicycle] The handlebars connect to the stem that connects to the fork housing the front wheel.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The whole assembly rotates about the steering axis, held by the headset bearings.
[src:biomass/bicycle] *Upright handlebars*, the norm in Europe and elsewhere until the 1970s, curve gently back towards the rider, offering a natural grip and comfortable upright position.
[src:biomass/bicycle] *Drop handlebars* "drop" as they curve forward and down, allowing the cyclist to use either a more aerodynamic "crouched" position or a more upright position.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Mountain bikes generally feature a 'straight handlebar' or 'riser bar' with varying degrees of sweep backward and centimeters rise upwards, as well as wider widths which can provide better handling due to increased leverage against the wheel.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Saddles also vary with rider preference, from the cushioned ones favored by short-distance riders to narrower saddles which allow more room for leg swings.
[src:biomass/bicycle] With comfort bikes and hybrids, cyclists sit high over the seat, their weight directed down onto the saddle, such that a wider and more cushioned saddle is preferable.
[src:biomass/bicycle] For racing bikes where the rider is bent over, weight is more evenly distributed between the handlebars and saddle, the hips are flexed, and a narrower and harder saddle is more efficient.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Differing saddle designs exist for male and female cyclists, accommodating the genders' differing anatomies and sit bone width measurements, although bikes are typically sold with saddles most appropriate for men.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Suspension seat posts and seat springs provide comfort by absorbing shock but can add to the overall weight of the bicycle.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A recumbent bicycle has a reclined chair-like seat that some riders find more comfortable than a saddle, especially riders who suffer from certain types of seat, back, neck, shoulder, or wrist pain.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Recumbent bicycles may have either under-seat or over-seat steering.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycle brakes may be rim brakes, in which friction pads are compressed against the wheel rims; hub brakes, where the mechanism is contained within the wheel hub; or disc brakes, where pads act on a rotor attached to the hub.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Most road bicycles use rim brakes, but some use disc brakes.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Disc brakes are more common for mountain bikes, tandems and recumbent bicycles than on other types of bicycles, due to their increased power, coupled with an increased weight and complexity.
[src:biomass/bicycle] With hand-operated brakes, force is applied to brake levers mounted on the handlebars and transmitted via Bowden cables or hydraulic lines to the friction pads, which apply pressure to the braking surface, causing friction which slows the bicycle down.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A rear hub brake may be either hand-operated or pedal-actuated, as in the back pedal *coaster brakes* which were popular in North America until the 1960s.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Track bicycles do not have brakes, because all riders ride in the same direction around a track which does not necessitate sharp deceleration.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Track riders are still able to slow down because all track bicycles are fixed-gear, meaning that there is no freewheel.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Without a freewheel, coasting is impossible, so when the rear wheel is moving, the cranks are moving.
[src:biomass/bicycle] To slow down, the rider applies resistance to the pedals, acting as a braking system which can be as effective as a conventional rear wheel brake, but not as effective as a front wheel brake.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycle suspension refers to the system or systems used to *suspend* the rider and all or part of the bicycle.
[src:biomass/bicycle] This serves two purposes: to keep the wheels in continuous contact with the ground, improving control, and to isolate the rider and luggage from jarring due to rough surfaces, improving comfort.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycle suspensions are used primarily on mountain bicycles, but are also common on hybrid bicycles, as they can help deal with problematic vibration from poor surfaces.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Suspension is especially important on recumbent bicycles, since while an upright bicycle rider can stand on the pedals to achieve some of the benefits of suspension, a recumbent rider cannot.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Basic mountain bicycles and hybrids usually have front suspension only, whilst more sophisticated ones also have rear suspension.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Road bicycles tend to have no suspension.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The wheel axle fits into fork ends in the frame and fork.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A pair of wheels may be called a wheelset, especially in the context of ready-built "off the shelf", performance-oriented wheels.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Tires vary enormously depending on their intended purpose.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Road bicycles typically use tires from 25 mm (1 in) to 35 mm (1.4 in) wide, sometimes completely smooth, or slick, and inflated to high pressure to roll fast on smooth surfaces.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Off-road tires are usually wider, from 30 mm (1.2 in) to 100 mm (4 in), and have treads for gripping in muddy conditions or metal studs for ice.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Some components, which are often optional accessories on sports bicycles, are standard features on utility bicycles to enhance their usefulness, comfort, safety and visibility.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Fenders with spoilers (mudflaps) protect the cyclist and moving parts from spray when riding through wet areas.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Germany, UK), fenders are called mudguards.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The chainguards protect clothes from oil on the chain while preventing clothing from being caught between the chain and crankset teeth.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Kick stands keep bicycles upright when parked, and bike locks deter theft.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Front-mounted baskets, front or rear luggage carriers or racks, and panniers mounted above either or both wheels can be used to carry equipment or cargo.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Parents sometimes add rear-mounted child seats, an auxiliary saddle fitted to the crossbar, or both to transport children.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycles can also be fitted with a hitch to tow a trailer for carrying cargo, a child, or both.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Toe-clips, toestraps and clipless pedals help keep the foot locked in the proper pedal position and enable cyclists to pull and push the pedals.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Technical accessories include cyclocomputers for measuring speed, distance, heart rate, GPS data etc.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Other accessories include lights, reflectors, mirrors, racks, trailers, bags, water bottles and cages, and bells.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycle lights, reflectors, and helmets are required by law in some geographic regions.
[src:biomass/bicycle] It is more common to see bicycles with bottle generators, dynamos, lights, fenders, racks and bells in Europe.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicyclists also have specialized form fitting and high visibility clothing.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Children's bicycles may be outfitted with cosmetic enhancements such as bike horns, streamers, and spoke beads.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Training wheels are sometimes used when learning to ride, but a dedicated balance bike teaches independent riding more effectively.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycle helmets can reduce injury in the event of a collision or accident, and a suitable helmet is legally required of riders in many jurisdictions.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Helmets may be classified as an accessory or as an item of clothing.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bike trainers are used to enable cyclists to cycle while the bike remains stationary.
[src:biomass/bicycle] They are frequently used to warm up before races or indoors when riding conditions are unfavorable.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A number of formal and industry standards exist for bicycle components to help make spare parts exchangeable and to maintain a minimum product safety.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The European Committee for Standardization (CEN) also has a specific Technical Committee, TC333, that defines European standards for cycles.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Their mandate states that CEN cycle standards shall harmonize with ISO standards.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Some CEN cycle standards were developed before ISO published their standards, leading to strong European influences in this area.
[src:biomass/bicycle] European cycle standards tend to describe minimum safety requirements, while ISO standards have historically harmonized parts geometry.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The bicycle industry or cycling industry can broadly be defined as the industry concerned with bicycles and cycling.
[src:biomass/bicycle] It includes at least bicycle manufacturers, part or component manufacturers, and accessory manufacturers.
[src:biomass/bicycle] It can also include distributors, retailers, bicycle organizations, bicycle event promoters, and bicycle related service providers.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The global bicycle industry generated sales of $66 billion in 2024.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Over 100 million bicycles are made each year, the top three manufacturing countries being China, India and Taiwan.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In 2025, the global market size was an estimated $116 billion.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Many bicycle brands do not manufacture their own product, but rather import and re-brand bikes manufactured by others, sometimes designing the bike, specifying the equipment, and providing quality control.
[src:biomass/bicycle] There are also brands that have, at different times, been manufacturers as well as re-branders: a company with manufacturing capability may market models made by other (overseas) factories, while simultaneously manufacturing bicycles in-house, for example, high-end models.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A bicycle can be kept in good condition for decades.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Like all products with mechanical moving parts, bicycles require regular maintenance and replacement of worn parts.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A bicycle is relatively simple compared with a car, so some cyclists choose to do at least part of the maintenance themselves.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Some components are easy to manage using relatively simple tools, while other components may require specialist manufacturer-dependent tools.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Keeping the tires correctly inflated can make a noticeable difference as to how the bike feels to ride.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycle tires usually have a marking on the sidewall indicating the pressure appropriate for that tire, from 100 to 1,400 kPa (15 to 200 psi).
[src:biomass/bicycle] Over the longer term, tires wear out, after 1,500 to 5,000 kilometres (900 to 3,000 miles); with punctures often the most visible sign of a worn tire.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Many community cycling organisations will check brakes and other basic parts for free, or bike shops at low cost.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Disc brakes can be cleaned but may need professional maintenance, but rim brakes are easier to adjust.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Chains can be washed with soapy water then lightly lubricated, but may need replacing after a couple of years.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Other parts, such as derailleur pivot points, can also be lubricated, but lightly as dirt may stick with too much oil.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Very few bicycle components can actually be repaired; replacement of the failing component is normal practice.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The most common roadside problem is a puncture of the tire's inner tube.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A patch kit may be employed to fix the puncture or the tube can be replaced, though the latter solution comes at a greater cost and waste of material.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Some brands of tires are much more puncture-resistant than others, often incorporating one or more layers of Kevlar; the downside of such tires is that they may be heavier and more difficult to fit and remove.
[src:biomass/bicycle] There are specialized bicycle tools for use both in the shop and at the roadside.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Special, thin wrenches are often required for maintaining various screw-fastened parts, specifically, the frequently lubricated ball-bearing "cones".
[src:biomass/bicycle] There are also cycling-specific multi-tools that combine many of these implements into a single compact device.
[src:biomass/bicycle] More specialized bicycle components may require more complex tools, including proprietary tools specific for a given manufacturer.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The bicycle has had a considerable effect on human society, in both the cultural and industrial realms.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Around the turn of the 20th century, bicycles reduced crowding in inner-city tenements by allowing workers to commute from more spacious dwellings in the suburbs.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycles allowed people to travel for leisure into the country, since bicycles were three times as energy efficient as walking and three to four times as fast.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In built-up cities around the world, urban planning uses cycling infrastructure like bikeways to reduce traffic congestion and air pollution.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A number of cities around the world have implemented schemes known as bicycle sharing systems or community bicycle programs.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The first of these was the White Bicycle plan in Amsterdam in 1965.
[src:biomass/bicycle] It was followed by yellow bicycles in La Rochelle and green bicycles in Cambridge.
[src:biomass/bicycle] These initiatives complement public transport systems and offer an alternative to motorized traffic to help reduce congestion and pollution.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In Europe, especially in the Netherlands and parts of Germany and Denmark, bicycle commuting is common.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In Copenhagen, a cyclists' organization runs a Cycling Embassy that promotes biking for commuting and sightseeing.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The United Kingdom has a tax break scheme (IR 176) that allows employees to buy a new bicycle tax free to use for commuting.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In the Netherlands, all train stations offer free bicycle parking, or a more secure parking place for a small fee, with the larger stations also offering bicycle repair shops.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Cycling is so popular that the parking capacity may be exceeded, such as in Delft, where the capacity is usually exceeded.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In Trondheim in Norway, the Trampe bicycle lift has been developed to encourage cyclists by giving assistance on a steep hill.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Buses in many cities have bicycle carriers mounted on the front.
[src:biomass/bicycle] There are towns in some countries where bicycle culture has been an integral part of the landscape for generations, even without much official support.
[src:biomass/bicycle] That is the case of Ílhavo, in Portugal.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In cities where bicycles are not integrated into the public transportation system, commuters often use bicycles as elements of a mixed-mode commute, where the bike is used to travel to and from train stations or other forms of rapid transit.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Some students who commute several miles drive a car from home to a campus parking lot, then ride a bicycle to class.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Folding bicycles are useful in these scenarios, as they are less cumbersome when carried aboard.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Los Angeles removed a small amount of seating on some trains to make more room for bicycles and wheelchairs.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Some US companies, notably in the tech sector, are developing both innovative cycle designs and cycle-friendliness in the workplace.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Foursquare, whose CEO Dennis Crowley "pedaled to pitch meetings ... [when he] was raising money from venture capitalists" on a two-wheeler, chose a new location for its New York headquarters "based on where biking would be easy".
[src:biomass/bicycle] Parking in the office was also integral to HQ planning.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Mitchell Moss, who runs the Rudin Center for Transportation Policy & Management at New York University, said in 2012: "Biking has become the mode of choice for the educated high tech worker".
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycles offer an important mode of transport in many developing countries.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Until recently, bicycles have been a staple of everyday life throughout Asian countries.
[src:biomass/bicycle] They are the most frequently used method of transport for commuting to work, school, shopping, and life in general.
[src:biomass/bicycle] They also offer a degree of exercise to keep individuals healthy.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycles are also celebrated in the visual arts.
[src:biomass/bicycle] An example of this is the Bicycle Film Festival, a film festival hosted all around the world.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycle poverty reduction is the concept that access to bicycles and the transportation infrastructure to support them can dramatically reduce poverty.
[src:biomass/bicycle] This has been demonstrated in various pilot projects in South Asia and Africa.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Experiments done in Africa (Uganda and Tanzania) and Sri Lanka on hundreds of households have shown that a bicycle can increase the income of a poor family by as much as 35%.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Transport, if analyzed for the cost–benefit analysis for rural poverty alleviation, has given one of the best returns in this regard.
[src:biomass/bicycle] For example, road investments in India were a staggering 3–10 times more effective than almost all other investments and subsidies in rural economy in the decade of the 1990s.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A road can ease transport on a macro level, while bicycle access supports it at the micro level.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In that sense, the bicycle can be one of the most effective means to eradicate poverty in poor nations.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The safety bicycle gave women unprecedented mobility, contributing to their emancipation in Western nations.
[src:biomass/bicycle] As bicycles became safer and cheaper, more women had access to the personal freedom that bicycles embodied, and so the bicycle came to symbolize the New Woman of the late 19th century, especially in Britain and the United States.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The bicycle craze in the 1890s also led to a movement for so-called rational dress, which helped liberate women from corsets and ankle-length skirts and other restrictive garments, substituting the then-shocking bloomers.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The bicycle was recognized by 19th-century feminists and suffragists as a "freedom machine" for women.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Anthony said in a *New York World* interview on 2 February 1896: "I think it has done more to emancipate woman than any one thing in the world.
[src:biomass/bicycle] I rejoice every time I see a woman ride by on a wheel.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Willard used a cycling metaphor to urge other suffragists to action.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In 1985, Georgena Terry started the first women-specific bicycle company.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Her designs featured frame geometry and wheel sizes chosen to better fit women, with shorter top tubes and more suitable reach.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycle manufacturing proved to be a training ground for other industries and led to the development of advanced metalworking techniques, both for the frames themselves and for special components such as ball bearings, washers, and sprockets.
[src:biomass/bicycle] These techniques later enabled skilled metalworkers and mechanics to develop the components used in early automobiles and aircraft.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Wilbur and Orville Wright, a pair of businessmen, ran the Wright Cycle Company which designed, manufactured and sold their bicycles during the bike boom of the 1890s.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In addition, bicycle makers adopted the annual model change (later derided as planned obsolescence, and usually credited to General Motors), which proved very successful.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Early bicycles were an example of conspicuous consumption, being adopted by the fashionable elites.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In addition, by serving as a platform for accessories, which could ultimately cost more than the bicycle itself, it paved the way for the likes of the Barbie doll.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycles helped create, or enhance, new kinds of businesses, such as bicycle messengers, traveling seamstresses, riding academies, and racing rinks.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Their board tracks were later adapted to early motorcycle and automobile racing.
[src:biomass/bicycle] There were a variety of new inventions, such as spoke tighteners, and specialized lights, socks and shoes, and even cameras, such as the Eastman Company's Poco.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Probably the best known and most widely used of these inventions, adopted well beyond cycling, is Charles Bennett's Bike Web, which came to be called the jock strap.
[src:biomass/bicycle] They also presaged a move away from public transit that would explode with the introduction of the automobile.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Starley's company became the Rover Cycle Company Ltd. in the late 1890s, and then renamed the Rover Company when it started making cars.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Morris Motors Limited (in Oxford) and Škoda also began in the bicycle business, as did the Wright brothers.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Alistair Craig, whose company eventually emerged to become the engine manufacturers Ailsa Craig, also started from manufacturing bicycles, in Glasgow in March 1885.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Now, almost none of them produce their own frames.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Many newer or smaller companies only design and market their products; with the actual production being completed elsewhere, often in Asia.
[src:biomass/bicycle] For example, over 60% of the world's bicycles are now made in China.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Despite this shift in production, as nations such as China and India become more wealthy, their own use of bicycles is declining due to the increasing affordability of cars and motorcycles.
[src:biomass/bicycle] One of the major reasons for the proliferation of Chinese-made bicycles in foreign markets is the lower cost of labor in China.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In line with the European financial crisis of that time, in 2011 the number of bicycle sales in Italy (1.75 million) surpassed the number of new car sales.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Emissions related to bicycles come from their production and in actual use from their source of power, that is the food consumed for pedalling, or the electricity required in the case of electric bicycles.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The materials used are mainly steel, aluminium, and carbon fibre.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Compared to other industries, the amounts of materials used are very small and the metals are well recyclable.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A further sources of emissions comes from the rubber pollution from tire wear.
[src:biomass/bicycle] A study with mountain bike tires measured off-road wear rates per pair of initially 3.6 grams rubber per 100 km, then decreasing to 2 g/1oo km, compared to cars with 11-12 g/100 km per vehicle on-road.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Early in its development, as with automobiles, there were restrictions on the operation of bicycles.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Along with advertising, and to gain free publicity, Albert A.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The 1968 Vienna Convention on Road Traffic of the United Nations considers a bicycle to be a vehicle, and a person controlling a bicycle (whether actually riding or not) is considered an operator or driver.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The traffic codes of many countries reflect these definitions and demand that a bicycle satisfy certain legal requirements before it can be used on public roads.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In many jurisdictions, it is an offense to use a bicycle that is not in a roadworthy condition.
[src:biomass/bicycle] In some countries, bicycles must have functioning front and rear lights when ridden after dark.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Bicycles are popular targets for theft, due to their value and ease of resale.
[src:biomass/bicycle] The number of bicycles stolen annually is difficult to quantify as a large number of crimes are not reported.
[src:biomass/bicycle] About 50% of the participants in the Montreal International Journal of Sustainable Transportation survey were subjected to a bicycle theft in their lifetime as active cyclists.
[src:biomass/bicycle] Most bicycles have serial numbers that can be recorded to verify identity in case of theft.
[src:biomass/biofuel] In general, biofuels emit fewer greenhouse gas emissions when burned in an engine and are generally considered carbon-neutral fuels as the carbon emitted has been captured from the atmosphere by the crops used in production.
[src:biomass/biofuel] However, life-cycle assessments of biofuels have shown large emissions associated with the potential land-use change required to produce additional biofuel feedstocks.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The outcomes of lifecycle assessments (LCAs) for biofuels are highly situational and dependent on many factors including the type of feedstock, production routes, data variations, and methodological choices.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Estimates about the climate impact from biofuels vary widely based on the methodology and exact situation examined.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Therefore, the climate change mitigation potential of biofuel varies considerably: in some scenarios biofuel emission levels are comparable to fossil fuels, and in other scenarios the use of biofuel results in negative emissions.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Global demand for biofuels is predicted to increase by 56% over 2022–2027.
[src:biomass/biofuel] By 2027 worldwide biofuel production is expected to supply 5.4% of the world's fuels for transport including 1% of aviation fuel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Demand for aviation biofuel is forecast to increase.
[src:biomass/biofuel] However some policy has been criticised for favoring ground transportation over aviation.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The IEA says that biofuel should particularly be used for applications which are difficult to electrify, such as shipping and aviation.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The two most common types of biofuel are bioethanol and biodiesel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The United States is the largest producer of bioethanol, while the EU is the largest producer of biodiesel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Meanwhile, Brazil produces and uses large amounts of bioethanol in vehicles, including in some flex-fuel cars exclusively available in Brazil.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The energy content in the global production of bioethanol and biodiesel is 2.2 and 1.8 EJ per year, respectively.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The term *biofuel* is used in different ways.
[src:biomass/biofuel] One definition is "Biofuels are biobased products, in solid, liquid, or gaseous forms.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Other publications reserve the term biofuel for *liquid* or *gaseous* fuels, used for transportation.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The IPCC Sixth Assessment Report defines *biofuel* as "A fuel, generally in liquid form, produced from biomass.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Biofuels include bioethanol from sugarcane, sugar beet or maize, and biodiesel from canola or soybeans.".
[src:biomass/biofuel] It goes on to define *biomass* in this context as "organic material excluding the material that is fossilized or embedded in geological formations".
[src:biomass/biofuel] This means that coal or other fossil fuels is not a form of biomass in this context.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Bioethanol is an alcohol made by fermentation, mostly from carbohydrates produced in sugar or starch crops such as maize, sugarcane, or sweet sorghum.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Cellulosic biomass, derived from non-food sources, such as trees and grasses, is also being developed as a feedstock for ethanol production.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Ethanol can be used as a fuel for vehicles in its pure form (E100), but it is usually used as a gasoline additive to increase octane ratings and improve vehicle emissions.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Biodiesel is produced from oils or fats using transesterification.
[src:biomass/biofuel] It can be used as a fuel for vehicles in its pure form (B100), but it is usually used as a diesel additive to reduce levels of particulates, carbon monoxide, and hydrocarbons from diesel-powered vehicles.
[src:biomass/biofuel] To avoid a "food versus fuel" dilemma, second-generation biofuels and third-generation biofuels (also called advanced biofuels or sustainable biofuels or drop-in biofuels) are made from feedstocks which do not directly compete with food or feed crop such as waste products and energy crops.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The feedstock used to make the fuels either grow on arable land but are byproducts of the main crop, or they are grown on marginal land.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Second-generation feedstocks also include straw, bagasse, perennial grasses, jatropha, waste vegetable oil, municipal solid waste and so forth.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Biologically produced alcohols, most commonly ethanol, and less commonly propanol and butanol, are produced by the action of microorganisms and enzymes through the fermentation of sugars or starches (easiest to produce) or cellulose (more difficult to produce).
[src:biomass/biofuel] The IEA estimates that ethanol production used 20% of sugar supplies and 13% of corn supplies in 2021.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Ethanol fuel is the most common biofuel worldwide, particularly in Brazil.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Alcohol fuels are produced by fermentation of sugars derived from wheat, corn, sugar beets, sugar cane, molasses and any sugar or starch from which alcoholic beverages such as whiskey, can be made (such as potato and fruit waste, etc.).
[src:biomass/biofuel] Production methods used are enzyme digestion (to release sugars from stored starches), fermentation of the sugars, distillation and drying.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The distillation process requires significant energy input to generate heat.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Heat is sometimes generated with unsustainable natural gas fossil fuel, but cellulosic biomass such as bagasse is the most common fuel in Brazil, while pellets, wood chips and also waste heat are more common in Europe.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Corn-to-ethanol and other food stocks has led to the development of cellulosic ethanol.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Ethanol fuel can be combined with gasoline to create a more environmentally friendly fuel though there are more viable substitutions to gasoline such as Butanol.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Methanol is currently produced from natural gas, a non-renewable fossil fuel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] In the future it is hoped to be produced from biomass as biomethanol.
[src:biomass/biofuel] This is technically feasible, but the production is currently being postponed for concerns that the economic viability is still pending.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The methanol economy is an alternative to the hydrogen economy to be contrasted with today's hydrogen production from natural gas.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Butanol (C 4H 9OH) is formed by ABE fermentation (acetone, butanol, ethanol) and experimental modifications of the process show potentially high net energy gains with biobutanol as the only liquid product.
[src:biomass/biofuel] *Escherichia coli* strains have also been successfully engineered to produce butanol by modifying their amino acid metabolism.
[src:biomass/biofuel] One drawback to butanol production in *E. coli* remains the high cost of nutrient rich media, however, recent work has demonstrated *E. coli* can produce butanol with minimal nutritional supplementation.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Biobutanol is sometimes called biogasoline, which is incorrect as it is chemically different, being an alcohol and not a hydrocarbon like gasoline.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Biodiesel is the most common biofuel in Europe.
[src:biomass/biofuel] It is produced from oils or fats using transesterification and is a liquid similar in composition to fossil/mineral diesel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Chemically, it consists mostly of fatty acid methyl (or ethyl) esters (FAMEs).
[src:biomass/biofuel] Feedstocks for biodiesel include animal fats, vegetable oils, soy, rapeseed, jatropha, mahua, mustard, flax, sunflower, palm oil, hemp, field pennycress, *Pongamia pinnata* and algae.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Pure biodiesel (B100, also known as "neat" biodiesel) currently reduces emissions with up to 60% compared to diesel Second generation B100.
[src:biomass/biofuel] As of 2020, researchers at Australia's CSIRO have been studying safflower oil as an engine lubricant, and researchers at Montana State University's Advanced Fuels Center in the US have been studying the oil's performance in a large diesel engine, with results described as a "breakthrough".
[src:biomass/biofuel] Biodiesel can be used in any diesel engine and modified equipment when mixed with mineral diesel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] It can also be used in its pure form (B100) in diesel engines, but some maintenance and performance problems may occur during wintertime utilization, since the fuel becomes somewhat more viscous at lower temperatures, depending on the feedstock used.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Electronically controlled 'common rail' and 'Unit Injector' type systems from the late 1990s onwards can only use biodiesel blended with conventional diesel fuel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] These engines have finely metered and atomized multiple-stage injection systems that are very sensitive to the viscosity of the fuel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Many current-generation diesel engines are designed to run on B100 without altering the engine itself, although this depends on the fuel rail design.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Since biodiesel is an effective solvent and cleans residues deposited by mineral diesel, engine filters may need to be replaced more often, as the biofuel dissolves old deposits in the fuel tank and pipes.
[src:biomass/biofuel] It also effectively cleans the engine combustion chamber of carbon deposits, helping to maintain efficiency.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Biodiesel is an oxygenated fuel, meaning it contains a reduced amount of carbon and higher hydrogen and oxygen content than fossil diesel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] This improves the combustion of biodiesel and reduces the particulate emissions from unburnt carbon.
[src:biomass/biofuel] However, using pure biodiesel may increase NOx-emissions Biodiesel is also safe to handle and transport because it is non-toxic and biodegradable, and has a high flash point of about 300 °F (148 °C) compared to petroleum diesel fuel, which has a flash point of 125 °F (52 °C).
[src:biomass/biofuel] In many European countries, a 5% biodiesel blend is widely used and is available at thousands of gas stations.
[src:biomass/biofuel] In France, biodiesel is incorporated at a rate of 8% in the fuel used by all French diesel vehicles.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Avril Group produces under the brand Diester, a fifth of 11 million tons of biodiesel consumed annually by the European Union.
[src:biomass/biofuel] It is the leading European producer of biodiesel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Green diesel can be produced from a combination of biochemical and thermochemical processes.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Conventional green diesel is produced through hydroprocessing biological oil feedstocks, such as vegetable oils and animal fats.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Recently, it is produced using series of thermochemical processes such as pyrolysis and hydroprocessing.
[src:biomass/biofuel] In the thermochemical route, syngas produced from gasification, bio-oil produced from pyrolysis or biocrude produced from hydrothermal liquefaction is upgraded to green diesel using hydroprocessing.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Hydroprocessing is the process of using hydrogen to reform a molecular structure.
[src:biomass/biofuel] For example, hydrocracking which is a widely used hydroprocessing technique in refineries is used at elevated temperatures and pressure in the presence of a catalyst to break down larger molecules, such as those found in vegetable oils, into shorter hydrocarbon chains used in diesel engines.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Green diesel may also be called renewable diesel, drop-in biodiesel, hydrotreated vegetable oil (HVO fuel) or hydrogen-derived renewable diesel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Unlike biodiesel, green diesel has exactly the same chemical properties as petroleum-based diesel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] It does not require new engines, pipelines or infrastructure to distribute and use, but has not been produced at a cost that is competitive with petroleum.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Gasoline versions are also being developed.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Green diesel is being developed in Louisiana and Singapore by ConocoPhillips, Neste Oil, Valero, Dynamic Fuels, and Honeywell UOP as well as Preem in Gothenburg, Sweden, creating what is known as Evolution Diesel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Straight unmodified edible vegetable oil is generally not used as fuel, but lower-quality oil has been used for this purpose.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Used vegetable oil is increasingly being processed into biodiesel, or (more rarely) cleaned of water and particulates and then used as a fuel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The IEA estimates that biodiesel production used 17% of global vegetable oil supplies in 2021.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Oils and fats reacted with 10 pounds of a short-chain alcohol (usually methanol) in the presence of a catalyst (usually sodium hydroxide [NaOH] can be hydrogenated to give a diesel substitute.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The resulting product is a straight-chain hydrocarbon with a high cetane number, low in aromatics and sulfur and does not contain oxygen.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Hydrogenated oils can be blended with diesel in all proportions.
[src:biomass/biofuel] They have several advantages over biodiesel, including good performance at low temperatures, no storage stability problems and no susceptibility to microbial attack.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Biogasoline can be produced biologically and thermochemically.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The enzymes converted the sugar into fatty acids and then turned these into hydrocarbons that were chemically and structurally identical to those found in commercial gasoline fuel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The thermochemical approach of producing biogasoline are similar to those used to produce biodiesel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Biogasoline may also be called drop-in gasoline or renewable gasoline.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Bioethers (also referred to as fuel ethers or oxygenated fuels) are cost-effective compounds that act as octane rating enhancers.
[src:biomass/biofuel] "Bioethers are produced by the reaction of reactive iso-olefins, such as iso-butylene, with bioethanol." Bioethers are created from wheat or sugar beets, and also be produced from the waste glycerol that results from the production of biodiesel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] They also enhance engine performance, while significantly reducing engine wear and toxic exhaust emissions.
[src:biomass/biofuel] By greatly reducing the amount of ground-level ozone emissions, they contribute to improved air quality.
[src:biomass/biofuel] In transportation fuel there are six ether additives: dimethyl ether (DME), diethyl ether (DEE), methyl *tert*-butyl ether (MTBE), ethyl *tert*-butyl ether (ETBE), *tert*-amyl methyl ether (TAME), and *tert*-amyl ethyl ether (TAEE).
[src:biomass/biofuel] The European Fuel Oxygenates Association identifies MTBE and ETBE as the most commonly used ethers in fuel to replace lead.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Ethers were introduced in Europe in the 1970s to replace the highly toxic compound.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Although Europeans still use bioether additives, the U.S.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Energy Policy Act of 2005 lifted a requirement for reformulated gasoline to include an oxygenate, leading to less MTBE being added to fuel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Although bioethers are likely to replace ethers produced from petroleum in the UK, it is highly unlikely they will become a fuel in and of itself due to the low energy density.
[src:biomass/biofuel] An aviation biofuel (also known as bio-jet fuel, sustainable aviation fuel (SAF), or bio-aviation fuel (BAF)) is a biofuel used to power aircraft.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The International Air Transport Association (IATA) considers it a key element in reducing the environmental impact of aviation.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Aviation biofuel is used to decarbonize medium and long-haul air travel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] These types of travel generate the most emissions.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Synthetic paraffinic kerosene (SPK) refers to any non-petroleum-based fuel designed to replace kerosene jet fuel, which is often, but not always, made from biomass.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Biofuels are biomass-derived fuels from plants, animals, or waste; depending on which type of biomass is used, they could lower CO2 emissions by 20–98% compared to conventional jet fuel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The first test flight using blended biofuel was in 2008, and in 2011, blended fuels with 50% biofuels were allowed on commercial flights.
[src:biomass/biofuel] In 2023 SAF production was 600 million liters, representing 0.2% of global jet fuel use.
[src:biomass/biofuel] By 2024, SAF production was to increase to 1.3 billion liters (1 million tonnes), representing 0.3% of global jet fuel consumption and 11% of global renewable fuel production.
[src:biomass/biofuel] This increase came as major US production facilities delayed their ramp-up until 2025, having initially been expected to reach 1.9 billion liters.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Small piston engines can be modified to burn ethanol.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Sustainable biofuels are an alternative to electrofuels.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Sustainable aviation fuel is certified as being sustainable by a third-party organisation.
[src:biomass/biofuel] SAF technology faces significant challenges due to feedstock constraints.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The oils and fats known as hydrotreated esters and fatty acids (Hefa), crucial for SAF production, are in limited supply as demand increases.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Although advanced e-fuels technology, which combines waste CO2 with clean hydrogen, presents a promising solution, it is still under development and comes with high costs.
[src:biomass/biofuel] To overcome these issues, SAF developers are exploring more readily available feedstocks such as woody biomass and agricultural and municipal waste, aiming to produce lower-carbon jet fuel more sustainably and efficiently.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Biogas is a mixture composed primarily of methane and carbon dioxide produced by the process of anaerobic digestion of organic material by micro-organisms.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Other trace components of this mixture includes water vapor, hydrogen sulfide, siloxanes, hydrocarbons, ammonia, oxygen, carbon monoxide, and nitrogen.
[src:biomass/biofuel] It can be produced either from biodegradable waste materials or by the use of energy crops fed into anaerobic digesters to supplement gas yields.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The solid byproduct, digestate, can be used as a biofuel or a fertilizer.
[src:biomass/biofuel] When CO2 and other impurities are removed from biogas, it is called biomethane.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The CO2 can also be combined with hydrogen in methanation to form more methane.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Biogas can be recovered from mechanical biological treatment waste processing systems.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Landfill gas, a less clean form of biogas, is produced in landfills through naturally occurring anaerobic digestion.
[src:biomass/biofuel] If it escapes into the atmosphere, it acts as a greenhouse gas.
[src:biomass/biofuel] In Sweden, "waste-to-energy" power plants capture methane biogas from garbage and use it to power transport systems.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Farmers can produce biogas from cattle manure via anaerobic digesters.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Syngas, a mixture of carbon monoxide, hydrogen and various hydrocarbons, is produced by partial combustion of biomass (combustion with an amount of oxygen that is not sufficient to convert the biomass completely to carbon dioxide and water).
[src:biomass/biofuel] Before partial combustion the biomass is dried and sometimes pyrolysed.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Syngas is more efficient than direct combustion of the original biofuel; more of the energy contained in the fuel is extracted.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Syngas may be burned directly in internal combustion engines, turbines or high-temperature fuel cells.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The wood gas generator, a wood-fueled gasification reactor, can be connected to an internal combustion engine.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Syngas can be used to produce methanol, dimethyl ether and hydrogen, or converted via the Fischer–Tropsch process to produce a diesel substitute, or a mixture of alcohols that can be blended into gasoline.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Gasification normally relies on temperatures greater than 700 °C.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Lower-temperature gasification is desirable when co-producing biochar, but results in syngas polluted with tar.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The term "biofuels" is also used for solid fuels that are made from biomass, even though this is less common.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Algae can be produced in ponds or tanks on land, and out at sea.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Algal fuels have high yields, a high ignition point, can be grown with minimal impact on fresh water resources, can be produced using saline water and wastewater, and are biodegradable and relatively harmless to the environment if spilled.
[src:biomass/biofuel] However, production requires large amounts of energy and fertilizer, the produced fuel degrades faster than other biofuels, and it does not flow well in cold temperatures.
[src:biomass/biofuel] By 2017, due to economic considerations, most efforts to produce fuel from algae have been abandoned or changed to other applications.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Third and fourth-generation biofuels also include biofuels that are produced by bioengineered organisms i.e. algae and cyanobacteria.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Algae and cyanobacteria will use water, carbon dioxide, and solar energy to produce biofuels.
[src:biomass/biofuel] This method of biofuel production is still at the research level.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The biofuels that are secreted by the bioengineered organisms are expected to have higher photon-to-fuel conversion efficiency, compared to older generations of biofuels.
[src:biomass/biofuel] One of the advantages of this class of biofuels is that the cultivation of the organisms that produce the biofuels does not require the use of arable land.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The disadvantages include the cost of cultivating the biofuel-producing organisms being very high.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Also, current methods of using algae often have worse environmental impacts than using other crops.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Recent research highlights that the transition to sustainable energy is reliant on the widespread adoption of third- and fourth-generation biofuels, which utilize non-food sources such as algae and incorporate advanced processes like artificial photosynthesis.
[src:biomass/biofuel] These alternatives are essential for climate change mitigation because they significantly reduce the land-use competition and sustainability risks associated with earlier biofuel generations.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Electrofuels and solar fuels may or may not be biofuels, depending on whether they contain biological elements.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Electrofuels are made by storing electrical energy in the chemical bonds of liquids and gases.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The primary targets are butanol, biodiesel, and hydrogen, but include other alcohols and carbon-containing gases such as methane and butane.
[src:biomass/biofuel] A solar fuel is a synthetic chemical fuel produced from solar energy.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Light is converted to chemical energy, typically by reducing protons to hydrogen, or carbon dioxide to organic compounds.
[src:biomass/biofuel] A bio-digester is a mechanized toilet that uses decomposition and sedimentation to turn human waste into a renewable fuel called biogas.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Biogas can be made from substances like agricultural waste and sewage.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The bio-digester uses a process called anaerobic digestion to produce biogas.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Anaerobic digestion uses a chemical process to break down organic matter with the use of microorganisms in the absence of oxygen to produce biogas.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The processes involved in anaerobic respiration are hydrolysis, acidogenesis, acetogenesis, and methanogenesis.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Global biofuel production was 81 Mtoe in 2017 which represented an annual increase of about 3% compared to 2010.
[src:biomass/biofuel] In 2017, the US was the largest biofuel producer in the world producing 37 Mtoe, followed by Brazil and South America at 23 Mtoe and Europe (mainly Germany) at 12 Mtoe.
[src:biomass/biofuel] An assessment from 2017 found that: "Biofuels will never be a major transport fuel as there is just not enough land in the world to grow plants to make biofuel for all vehicles.
[src:biomass/biofuel] In 2021, worldwide biofuel production provided 4.3% of the world's fuels for transport, including a very small amount of aviation biofuel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] By 2027, worldwide biofuel production is expected to supply 5.4% of the world's fuels for transport including 1% of aviation fuel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The US, Europe, Brazil and Indonesia are driving the majority of biofuel consumption growth.
[src:biomass/biofuel] This demand for biodiesel, renewable diesel and biojet fuel is projected to increase by 44% (21 billion litres) over 2022-2027.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Issues relating to biofuel are social, economic, environmental and technical problems that may arise from biofuel production and use.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Social and economic issues include the "food vs fuel" debate and the need to develop responsible policies and economic instruments to ensure sustainable biofuel production.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Farming for biofuels feedstock can be detrimental to the environment if not done sustainably.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Environmental concerns include deforestation, biodiversity loss and soil erosion as a result of land clearing for biofuels agriculture.
[src:biomass/biofuel] While biofuels can contribute to reduction in global carbon emissions, indirect land use change for biofuel production can have the inverse effect.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Technical issues include possible modifications necessary to run the engine on biofuel, as well as energy balance and efficiency.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The International Resource Panel outlined the wider and interrelated factors that need to be considered when deciding on the relative merits of pursuing one biofuel over another.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The IRP concluded that not all biofuels perform equally in terms of their effect on climate, energy security and ecosystems, and suggested that environmental and social effects need to be assessed throughout the entire life-cycle.
[src:biomass/biofuel] In general, biofuels emit fewer greenhouse gas emissions when burned in an engine and are generally considered carbon-neutral fuels as the carbon they emit has been captured from the atmosphere by the crops used in biofuel production.
[src:biomass/biofuel] They can have greenhouse gas emissions ranging from as low as -127.1 gCO2eq per MJ when carbon capture is incorporated into their production to those exceeding 95 gCO2eq per MJ when land-use change is significant.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Several factors are responsible for the variation in emission numbers of biofuel, such as feedstock and its origin, fuel production technique, system boundary definitions, and energy sources.
[src:biomass/biofuel] However, many government policies, such as those by the European Union and the UK, require that biofuels have at least 65% greenhouse gas emissions savings (or 70% if it is renewable fuels of non-biological origins) relative to fossil fuels.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Life-cycle assessments of first-generation biofuels have shown large emissions associated with the potential land-use change required to produce additional biofuel feedstocks.
[src:biomass/biofuel] If no land-use change is involved, first-generation biofuels can—on average—have lower emissions than fossil fuels.
[src:biomass/biofuel] However, biofuel production can compete with food crop production.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Up to 40% of corn produced in the United States is used to make ethanol and worldwide 10% of all grain is turned into biofuel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] A 50% reduction in grain used for biofuels in the US and Europe would replace all of Ukraine's grain exports.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Several studies have shown that reductions in emissions from biofuels are achieved at the expense of other impacts, such as acidification, eutrophication, water footprint and biodiversity loss.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Second-generation biofuels are thought to increase environmental sustainability since the non-food part of plants is being used to produce second-generation biofuels instead of being disposed of.
[src:biomass/biofuel] But the use of second-generation biofuels increases the competition for lignocellulosic biomass, increasing the cost of these biofuels.
[src:biomass/biofuel] In theory, third-generation biofuels, produced from algae, shouldn't harm the environment more than first- or second-generation biofuels due to lower changes in land use and the fact that they do not require pesticide use for production.
[src:biomass/biofuel] When looking at the data however, it has been shown that the environmental cost to produce the infrastructure and energy required for third generation biofuel production, are higher than the benefits provided from the biofuels use.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The European Commission has officially approved a measure to phase out palm oil-based biofuels by 2030.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Unsustainable palm oil agriculture has caused significant environmental and social problems, including deforestation and pollution.
[src:biomass/biofuel] The production of biofuels can be very energy intensive, which, if generated from non-renewable sources, can heavily mitigate the benefits gained through biofuel use.
[src:biomass/biofuel] A solution proposed to solve this issue is to supply biofuel production facilities with excess nuclear energy, which can supplement the power provided by fossil fuels.
[src:biomass/biofuel] This can provide a carbon inexpensive solution to help reduce the environmental impacts of biofuel production.
[src:biomass/biofuel] As farmers worldwide respond to higher crop prices in order to maintain the global food supply-and-demand balance, pristine lands are cleared to replace the food crops that were diverted elsewhere to biofuels' production.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Because natural lands, such as rainforests and grasslands, store carbon in their soil and biomass as plants grow each year, clearance of wilderness for new farms translates to a net increase in greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Due to this off-site change in the carbon stock of the soil and the biomass, indirect land use change has consequences in the greenhouse gas (GHG) balance of a biofuel.
[src:biomass/biofuel] Other authors have also argued that indirect land use changes produce other significant social and environmental impacts, affecting biodiversity, water quality, food prices and supply, land tenure, worker migration, and community and cultural stability.
[src:biomass/biogas] Biogas is considered to be a renewable energy resource as the methane can be combusted to release energy.
[src:biomass/biogas] This energy release allows biogas to be used as a fuel.
[src:biomass/biogas] Biogas and its derivatives are used for multiple purposes including heat for cooking, electricity generation, and as a vehicle fuel.
[src:biomass/biogas] At a high level, biogas is a carbon-neutral fuel in so far as emissions of carbon dioxide from its combustion are matched by carbon dioxide pulled from the atmosphere to produce biomass.
[src:biomass/biogas] In practice, the carbon intensity of biogas can vary depending on emissions from the production of biomass and the processes used to produce and upgrade biogas.
